{"title_page": "National responses to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic", "text_new": "{{pp-semi-indef|small=yes}}\n{{Short description|Internal responses of the nations of the world.}}\n{{About|government responses to the outbreak|information on the status of the outbreak by country|2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic by country and territory|criticism|Criticism of response to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n{{overly detailed|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic sidebar|expanded=international}}\n[[File:Tree- How Covid-19 spreads.png|upright=1.4|thumb|Illustration showing how COVID-19 spreads and the impact of isolation on it.]]\n'''National responses to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic''' have been varied, and have included containment measures such as [[lockdown|lockdowns]], [[quarantine|quarantines]], and [[curfew|curfews]]. As of late April, there are <!-- use a round figure here, nearest to 100,000 -->2.4 million cases of [[COVID-19]] and over <!-- use a round figure here, nearest to 100 -->164,300 deaths in 185 countries around the world. The most affected countries in terms of confirmed cases being the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States|United States]], [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Spain|Spain]], [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Italy|Italy]], [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in France|France]], [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Germany|Germany]], the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United Kingdom|United Kingdom]], [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Turkey|Turkey]] and [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in mainland China|China]].<ref>{{cite url |title=COVID-19 Dashboard by the Center for Systems Science and Engineering (CSSE) at Johns Hopkins University (JHU) |url=https://www.arcgis.com/apps/opsdashboard/index.html#/bda7594740fd40299423467b48e9ecf6 |work=John Hopkins University |access-date=20 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Guti\u00e9rrez |first1=Pablo |title=Coronavirus map: how Covid-19 is spreading across the world |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/ng-interactive/2020/mar/24/coronavirus-map-how-covid-19-is-spreading-across-the-world |work=The Guardian |access-date=20 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Lockdowns ==\nThis listshows worldwide [[curfew]]s and similar restrictions (known as [[stay-at-home order]]s, shelter-in-place orders, [[Shutdown (economics)|shutdowns]]/[[lockdown]]s) related to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] and established to prevent further spread of the [[severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2]] (SARS-CoV-2), which causes [[coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]].\n\nThe pandemic has resulted in the largest amount of shutdowns/lockdowns worldwide at the same time in [[history]].{{cn|date=April 2020}} Curfews and lockdowns between and within nations are of varying stringency.\n\n<div style=\"float:left;\">{{2020 coronavirus pandemic lockdowns}}</div>\n{{clear}}\n\n==Africa==\n=== South Africa ===\n{{main|2020 coronavirus pandemic in South Africa}}\n{{Expand section|date=April 2020}}\n{{multiple image\n | width = 160\n | footer = [[Greenmarket Square]] in [[Cape Town]], South Africa seven days before (left) and on the first day (right) of the COVID 19 national lockdown. After the lockdown the [[market stall]] traders that normally setup on the square everyday are not present and only people exempt from the lockdown (security personnel and municipal employees) can be seen. \n | image1 = Greenmarket square 20200320.jpg\n | alt1 = Greenmarket Square as it normally appears with many market stalls, seven days before the lockdown.\n | caption1 = \n | image2 =  Greenmarket Square 20200327.jpg\n | alt2 = On the first day of the lockdown only people exempt from the lockdown (security personnel and sanitation workers) can be seen.\n | caption2 = \n}}\n[[President of South Africa|President]] [[Cyril Ramaphosa]] declared that South Africa would undergo a national lockdown, for a period of 21 days, from 26 March to 16 April 2020. This drastic measure was intended to help keep the viral infection rate as low as possible and save lives.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailymaverick.co.za/article/2020-03-23-south-africa-on-lockdown-from-thursday/|title=National Address: South Africa on lockdown from Thursday|first=Cyril|last=Ramaphosa|website=Daily Maverick|accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref> On Thursday 9 April, President Ramaphosa announced an extension of two weeks to the lockdown, until the end of April.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://businesstech.co.za/news/government/388743/south-africas-coronavirus-lockdown-extended-by-2-weeks/|title=South Africa\u2019s coronavirus lockdown extended by 2 weeks|first=Cyril|last=Ramaphosa|website=BusinessTechSA|accessdate=16 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Other countries and territories===\n{{div col|colwidth=15em}}\n\n* [[Image:Flag of Algeria.svg|25px]] '''[[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Algeria#Timeline|Algeria]]'''\n* [[Image:Flag of Angola.svg|25px]] '''[[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Angola#Timeline|Angola]]'''\n* [[Image:Flag of Benin.svg|25px]] '''[[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Benin#Timeline|Benin]]'''\n* [[Image:Flag of Botswana.svg|25px]] '''[[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Botswana#Prevention|Botswana]]'''\n* [[Image:Flag of Burkina Faso.svg|25px]] '''[[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Burkina Faso#Timeline|Burkina Faso]]'''\n* [[Image:Flag of Burundi.svg|25px]] '''[[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Burundi#Prevention|Burundi]]'''\n* [[Image:Flag of Cameroon.svg|25px]] '''[[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Cameroon#Government measures|Cameroon]]'''\n* [[Image:Flag of Canary Islands.svg|25px]] '''[[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the Canary Islands|Canary Islands]]'''\n* [[Image:Flag of Cape Verde.svg|25px]] '''[[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Cape Verde#Prevention|Cape Verde]]'''\n* [[Image:Flag of Central African Republic.svg|25px]] '''[[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the Central African Republic|Central African Republic]]'''\n* [[Image:Flag of Chad.svg|25px]] '''[[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Chad#Response|Chad]]'''\n* [[Image:Flag of Democratic Republic of the Congo.svg|25px]] '''[[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the Democratic Republic of the Congo#Prevention measures|Democratic Republic of the Congo]]'''\n* [[Image:Flag of Djibouti.svg|25px]] '''[[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Djibouti#Prevention|Djibouti]]'''\n* [[Image:Flag of Egypt.svg|25px]] '''[[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Egypt#Timeline|Egypt]]'''\n* [[Image:Flag of Equatorial Guinea.svg|25px]] '''[[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Equatorial Guinea#Response|Equatorial Guinea]]'''\n* [[Image:Flag of Eritrea.svg|25px]] '''[[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Eritrea#Prevention measures|Eritrea]]'''\n* [[Image:Flag of Eswatini.svg|25px]] '''[[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Eswatini#Timeline|Eswatini]]'''\n* [[Image:Flag of Ethiopia.svg|25px]] '''[[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Ethiopia#Reactions|Ethiopia]]'''\n* [[Image:Flag of Gabon.svg|25px]] '''[[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Gabon#Timeline|Gabon]]'''\n* [[Image:Flag of Gambia.svg|25px]] '''[[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Gambia#Government measures|Gambia]]'''\n* [[Image:Flag of Ghana.svg|25px]] '''[[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Ghana#Timeline|Ghana]]'''\n* [[Image:Flag of Guinea.svg|25px]] '''[[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Guinea|Guinea]]'''\n* [[Image:Flag of Guinea-Bissau.svg|25px]] '''[[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Guinea-Bissau|Guinea-Bissau]]'''\n* [[Image:Flag of Ivory Coast.svg|25px]] '''[[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Ivory Coast#Timeline|Ivory Coast]]'''\n* [[Image:Flag of Kenya.svg|25px]] '''[[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Kenya#Government response|Kenya]]'''\n* [[Image:Flag of Liberia.svg|25px]] '''[[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Liberia#Response|Liberia]]'''\n* [[Image:Flag of Libya.svg|25px]] '''[[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Libya#Timeline|Libya]]'''\n* [[Image:Flag of Madagascar.svg|25px]] '''[[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Madagascar#Prevention measures|Madagascar]]'''\n* [[Image:Flag of Malawi.svg|25px]] '''[[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Malawi#Government response|Malawi]]'''\n* [[Image:Flag of Mali.svg|25px]] '''[[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Mali#Prevention measures|Mali]]'''\n* [[Image:Flag of Mauritania.svg|25px]] '''[[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Mauritania#Timeline|Mauritania]]'''\n* [[Image:Flag of Mauritius.svg|25px]] '''[[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Mauritius#Response|Mauritius]]'''\n* [[Image:Flag of Mayotte.svg|25px]] '''[[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Mayotte#Timeline|Mayotte]]'''\n* [[Image:Flag of Morocco.svg|25px]] '''[[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Morocco#Responses|Morocco]]'''\n* [[Image:Flag of Mozambique.svg|25px]] '''[[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Mozambique#Timeline|Mozambique]]'''\n* [[Image:Flag of Namibia.svg|25px]] '''[[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Namibia#Government responses|Namibia]]'''\n* [[Image:Flag of Niger.svg|25px]] '''[[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Niger#Timeline|Niger]]'''\n* [[Image:Flag of Nigeria.svg|25px]] '''[[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Nigeria#Reactions|Nigeria]]'''\n* [[Image:Flag of Republic of the Congo.svg|25px]] '''[[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Republic of the Congo#Timeline|Republic of the Congo]]'''\n* [[Image:Flag of Rwanda.svg|25px]] '''[[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Rwanda#Government reaction|Rwanda]]'''\n* [[Image:Flag of S\u00e3o Tom\u00e9 and Pr\u00edncipe.svg|25px]] '''[[2020 coronavirus pandemic in S\u00e3o Tom\u00e9 and Pr\u00edncipe#Prevention|S\u00e3o Tom\u00e9 and Pr\u00edncipe]]'''\n* [[Image:Flag of Senegal.svg|25px]] '''[[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Senegal#Timeline|Senegal]]'''\n* [[Image:Flag of Seychelles.svg|25px]] '''[[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Seychelles#Responses|Seychelles]]'''\n* [[Image:Flag of Sierra Leone.svg|25px]] '''[[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Sierra Leone#Response|Sierra Leone]]'''\n* [[Image:Flag of Somalia.svg|25px]] '''[[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Somalia#Response|Somalia]]'''\n* [[Image:Flag of South Sudan.svg|25px]] '''[[2020 coronavirus pandemic in South Sudan#Prevention efforts|South Sudan]]'''\n* [[Image:Flag of Sudan.svg|25px]] '''[[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Sudan|Sudan]]'''\n* [[Image:Flag of Tanzania.svg|25px]] '''[[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Tanzania#Timeline|Tanzania]]'''\n* [[Image:Flag of Togo.svg|25px]] '''[[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Togo#Response|Togo]]'''\n* [[Image:Flag of Tunisia.svg|25px]] '''[[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Tunisia|Tunisia]]'''\n* [[Image:Flag of Uganda.svg|25px]] '''[[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Uganda#Prevention|Uganda]]'''\n* [[Image:Flag of Western Sahara.svg|25px]] '''[[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Western Sahara|Western Sahara]]'''\n* [[Image:Flag of Zambia.svg|25px]] '''[[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Zambia|Zambia]]'''\n* [[Image:Flag of Zimbabwe.svg|25px]] '''[[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Zimbabwe#Prevention measures and effects|Zimbabwe]]'''\n\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Asia==\n=== China ===\n{{Main|2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic in mainland China}}\n{{summarize section|date=April 2020}}\n\n[[File:Changchun Longjia Airport Terminal 2 Security Check (20200126) (cropped).jpg|thumb|right|Masked passengers undergoing temperature checks at [[Changchun Longjia International Airport|Changchun Longjia Airport]] in northeast China]]\nThe first person known to have fallen ill due to the new virus was in Wuhan on 1 December 2019.<ref name=\"AutoDW-67\"/> A public notice on the outbreak was released by Wuhan health authority on 31 December; the initial notice informed Wuhan residents that there was no clear evidence of human-to-human transmission of the virus, that the disease is preventable and controllable, and that people can wear masks when going out.<ref name=\"AutoDW-68\"/> WHO was informed of the outbreak on the same day.<ref name=\"AutoDW-69\"/> On 7 January 2020, the Chinese [[Politburo Standing Committee of the Communist Party of China|Communist Party Politburo Standing Committee]] discussed novel coronavirus prevention and control.<ref name=\"Xi's meeting\"/><ref name=\"Xi's meeting 2\"/>\n\nThe Wuhan government, which announced a number of new measures such as cancelling the [[Chinese New Year]] celebrations, in addition to measures such as checking the temperature of passengers at transport terminals first introduced on 14 January.<ref name=\"AutoDW-71\"/> A [[2020 Hubei lockdowns|quarantine]] was announced on 23 January 2020 stopping travel in and out of Wuhan.<ref name=\"channelnewsasia12306684\"/> A leading group tasked with the prevention and control of the novel coronavirus pandemic was established on 26 January, led by [[Premier of the People's Republic of China|Chinese Premier]] [[Li Keqiang]].<ref name=\"Premier leading\"/><ref name=\"Premier visiting\"/> The leading group decided to extend the Spring Festival [[Golden Week (China)|holiday]] to contain the outbreak.<ref name=\"AutoDW-72\"/>\n\nChina Customs started requiring that all passengers entering and exiting China fill in an extra health declaration form from 26 January. The health declaration form was mentioned in China's Frontier Health and Quarantine Law, granting the customs rights to require it if needed.<ref name=\"AutoDW-73\"/><ref name=\"xinhuanet1125502381\"/><ref name=\"20200126cgtn\"/> On 27 January, the [[General Office of the State Council]] of China, declared a nation-wide extension on the New Year holiday and the postponement of the coming spring semester. The office extended the previously scheduled [[Public holidays in China|public holiday]] from 30 January, to 2 February, while it said school openings for the spring semester would be announced in the future.<ref name=\"xinhuanet138735904\"/>\n\nHong Kong's [[Chief Executive of Hong Kong|Chief Executive]] [[Carrie Lam]] declared an emergency at a press conference on 25 January, saying [[Government of Hong Kong|the government]] would close primary and secondary schools for two more weeks on top of the previously scheduled New Year holiday, pushing the date for school reopening to 17 February.<ref name=\"scmp3047645\"/><ref name=\"apnews-b2810ce\"/> Macau closed several museums and libraries, and prolonged the New Year holiday break to 11 February for higher education institutions and 10 February for others.<ref name=\"xinhuanet1125500373\"/>\n\n[[File:A Screen Display During Wuhan Coronavirus Outbreak.jpg|thumb|right|A screen display in [[Hefei]] showing \"early detection, early reporting, early quarantine, early diagnosis, early treatment\" during the coronavirus pandemic|link=Special:FilePath/A_Screen_Display_During_Wuhan_coronavirus_pandemic.jpg]]\nOn 1 February 2020, Xinhua News reported that China's [[Supreme People's Procuratorate]] (SPP) has \"asked procuratorates nationwide to fully play their role to create a favourable judicial environment in the fight against the novel coronavirus pandemic.\" This includes severe punishments for those found guilty of dereliction of duty and the withholding of information for officials. Tougher charges were proscribed for commercial criminal activities such as \"the pushing up of prices, profiteering and severely disturbing market order\" along with the \"production and sale of fake and shoddy protective equipment and medicines.\" Prosecuting actions against patients who deliberately spread the infection or refuse examination or compulsory isolation along with threats of violence against medical personnel were also urged. The statement also included urging to prosecute those found \"fabricating coronavirus-related information that may lead to panic among the public, making up and spreading rumours about the virus, sabotaging the implementation of the law and endangering public security\" and also stressed \"harshly punishing the illegal hunting of wildlife under state protection, as well as improving inspection and quarantine measures for fresh food and meat products.\"<ref name=\"xinhuanet138747853\"/>\n\n==== Quarantine ====\n\n{{Main|2020 Hubei lockdowns}}\nOn 23 January 2020, a [[quarantine]] on [[lockdown|travel in and out]] of Wuhan was imposed in an effort to stop the spread of the virus out of Wuhan. Flights, trains, public buses, the metro system, and long-distance coaches were suspended indefinitely. Large-scale gatherings and group tours were also suspended.<ref name=\"channelnewsasia12306684\" /> By 24 January 2020, a total of 15 cities in Hubei, including Wuhan, were placed under similar quarantine measures.<ref name=\":0\"/>\n\nBefore the quarantine began, some in Wuhan questioned the reliability of the figures from the Chinese government as well as the government response, with some calling for quarantine,<ref name=\"bbc51205074\"/> and a post also showed sick people and three dead bodies covered in white sheets on the floor of a hospital on 24 January, although many such posts in Weibo about the epidemic have since been deleted.<ref name=\"20200128nytimes\"/><ref name=\"20200126telegraph\"/> Due to quarantine measures, Wuhan residents rushed to stockpile essential goods, food, and fuel; prices rose significantly.<ref name=\"20200123reuters\"/><ref name=\"AutoDW-78\"/> 5,000,000 people left Wuhan, with 9,000,000 left in the city.<ref name=\"abc11902378\"/> The city of [[Shantou]] in Guangdong declared a partial lockdown on 26 January,<ref name=\"AutoDW-79\"/> though this was reversed two hours later.<ref name=\"20200126reuters\"/> Local authorities in Beijing and several other major cities, including [[Hangzhou]], [[Guangzhou]], Shanghai, and [[Shenzhen]], announced on the same day that these cities will not impose a lockdown similar to those in Hubei province.<ref name=\"bjnews680010\"/> \n\nBy 6 February 2020, a total of four Zhejiang cities\u2014Wenzhou, Hangzhou, Ningbo, and Taizhou\u2014were under the \"passport\" system, allowing only one person per household to leave their home every two days. These restrictions apply to over 30&nbsp;million people.<ref name=\"SCMP 20200206\" />\n\n<gallery mode=\"packed\" heights=\"150px\">\nFile:Citizens of Wuhan lining up outside of a drug store to buy masks during the Wuhan coronavirus outbreak.jpg|People queueing outside a Wuhan pharmacy to buy face masks and medical supplies\nFile:Wuhan citizens rush to buy vegetables during Wuhan coronavirus outbreak.jpg|Residents of Wuhan wearing masks rushed out to nearby markets to buy vegetables and other food on 23 January during the outbreak\nFile:Last train of Wuhan metro before authorities lock down the city for the Wuhan coronavirus outbreak.jpg|Residents of Wuhan waiting for the last train of the city's metro on 10&nbsp;am, 22 January\n</gallery>\n\n==== Speciality hospitals ====\n[[File:Wuhan Huoshenshan Hospital under construction 02.jpg|right|thumb|Construction site of [[Huoshenshan Hospital]] as it appeared on 24 January.]]\nA speciality hospital named [[Huoshenshan Hospital]] has been constructed as a countermeasure against the outbreak and to better quarantine the patients. Wuhan City government had demanded that a state-owned enterprise construct such a hospital \"at the fastest speed\" comparable to that of the [[Timeline of the SARS outbreak|SARS outbreak in 2003]].<ref name=\"Outbreak\"/> Upon opening, the speciality hospital had 1,000 beds<ref name=\"20200128www\"/> and took up 30,000 square metres. The hospital is modelled after the {{ill|Xiaotangshan Hospital|2=zh|3=\u5c0f\u6c64\u5c71\u533b\u9662|preserve=1}}, which was fabricated for the SARS outbreak of 2003, itself built in only seven days.<ref name=\"Xinhua Huoshenshan\"/><ref name=\"20200124theguardian-plans\"/> \n\nOn 24 January 2020, the authority announced that they would convert an empty building in [[Huangzhou District]], Huanggang to a 1,000-bed hospital named [[Dabie Mountain Regional Medical Centre]]. Works began the next day by 500 personnel and the building began accepting patients on 28 January 2020 at 10:30&nbsp;pm.<ref name=\"metro12142899\"/> In Wuhan, authorities seized dormitories, offices and hospitals to create more beds for patients.<ref name=\"AutoDW-185\"/> On 25 January authorities announced plans for [[Leishenshan Hospital]], a second speciality hospital, with a capacity of 1,600 beds;<ref name=\"bjnews681160\"/> operations are scheduled to start by 6 February.<ref name=\"yicai20200131\"/><ref name=\"people33744294\"/> The hospital opened on 8 February.<ref name=\"CGTN09\">{{cite news|date=9 February 2020|url=https://america.cgtn.com/2020/02/09/first-30-viral-pneumonia-patients-admitted-in-leishenshan-hospital|title=First 30 viral pneumonia patients admitted in Leishenshan Hospital|publisher=CGTN|accessdate=10 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nBy 16 February 2020, 217 teams of a total of 25,633 medical workers from across China went to Wuhan and other cities in Hubei to help open up more facilities and treat patients.<ref name=\"AutoDW-118\"/> A total of 14 temporary hospitals were constructed in China in total, but all were reported to have closed after the crisis was determined be under control on 10 March 2020.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-china-51813876 |title=Coronavirus: China says disease 'curbed' in Wuhan and Hubei | date=10 March 2020 |work=BBC}}</ref> \n\n==== Censorship and police responses ====\n{{See also|Censorship in China|Internet censorship in China|Human rights issues during the 2019\u201320 coronavirus_pandemic#Censorship}}\n[[File:\u674e\u6587\u4eae\u7684\u8bad\u8beb\u4e66.png|right|thumb|Document issued by the Wuhan Police ordering [[Li Wenliang]] to stop \"spreading rumours\" about a possible 'SARS virus' dated 3 January.]]\nThe early response by city authorities was criticised as prioritising a control of information that might be unfavorable for local officials over public safety, and China was also criticised for cover-ups and\ndownplaying the initial discovery and severity of the outbreak. By the time China had informed the WHO of the new coronavirus on 31 December 2019, ''[[The New York Times]]'' reported that the government was still keeping \"its own citizens in the dark\".<ref name=\"TrueCost\">{{Cite web|url= https://nationalpost.com/news/the-true-cost-of-chinas-coronavirus-cover-up-how-state-censorship-let-the-outbreak-spread |title=The true cost of China's coronavirus cover-up: How state censorship let the outbreak spread |publisher=Financial Times |via=Nationalpost.com |date=7 February 2020 |accessdate=7 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"FaceXi\">{{cite news |url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/01/23/asia/wuhan-china-coronavirus-sars-response-intl-hnk/index.html |title=Wuhan is the latest crisis to face China's Xi, and it's exposing major flaws in his model of control |last=Griffiths |first=James |publisher=CNN |access-date=10 February 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200208194710/https://www.cnn.com/2020/01/23/asia/wuhan-china-coronavirus-sars-response-intl-hnk/index.html |archive-date=8 February 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> Observers have attributed this to the censorship institutional structure of the country's press and Internet, exacerbated by China's [[paramount leader]] [[Xi Jinping]]'s crackdown on independent oversight such as journalism and social media that left senior officials with inaccurate information on the outbreak and \"contributed to a prolonged period of inaction that allowed the virus to spread\".<ref name=\"TrueCost\" /><ref name=\"FaceXi\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/01/29/opinion/coronavirus-china-government.html|access-date=2 March 2020|\ntitle=Coronavirus Spreads, and the World Pays for China's Dictatorship|date=29 January 2020|first1=Nicholas|last1=Kristof|work=[[The New York Times]]}}</ref><ref name=\"auto5\">{{cite web |url=https://www.newstatesman.com/world/asia/2020/01/china-s-slow-response-coronavirus-has-shown-weakness-its-centralised-model |title=China's slow response to coronavirus has shown the weakness of its centralised model |website=New Statesman |access-date=10 February 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200128134506/https://www.newstatesman.com/world/asia/2020/01/china-s-slow-response-coronavirus-has-shown-weakness-its-centralised-model |archive-date=28 January 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nA group of eight medical personnel, including [[Li Wenliang]], an ophthalmologist from Wuhan Central Hospital who in late December posted warnings on a new coronavirus strain akin to SARS, were taken into custody by Wuhan police and threatened with prosecution for \"spreading rumours\" for likening it to SARS.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.worldjournal.com/6771702/article-\u65b0\u51a0\u80ba\u708e\u7b2c\u4e00\u500b\u5439\u54e8\u8005-\u674e\u6587\u4eae\u91ab\u5e2b\u904e\u4e16/ |title=\u65b0\u51a0\u80ba\u708e\u5439\u54e8\u91ab\u5e2b \u674e\u6587\u4eae\u75c5\u901d \u6c11\u773e\u6fc0\u61a4|date=7 February 2020|website=\u4e16\u754c\u65b0\u805e\u7db2|language=zh-TW|access-date=10 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-china-51403795|title=Coronavirus kills Chinese whistleblower doctor|date=7 February 2020|publisher=BBC News|access-date=10 February 2020}}</ref>  Li Wenliang later died of the disease on 7 February, and was widely hailed as a whistleblower in China, but some of the trending hashtags on [[Sina Weibo|Weibo]] such as \"Wuhan government owes Dr Li Wenliang an apology\" and \"We want freedom of speech\" were blocked.<ref name=\"auto3\">{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/01/27/technology/china-coronavirus-censorship-social-media.html |title=As Virus Spreads, Anger Floods Chinese Social Media |last=Zhong |first=Raymond |date=27 January 2020 |work=[[The New York Times]] |access-date=10 February 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200128115157/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/01/27/technology/china-coronavirus-censorship-social-media.html |archive-date=28 January 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-china-51409801|title=Li Wenliang: Coronavirus death of Wuhan doctor sparks outpouring of anger|date=7 February 2020|publisher=[[BBC News]]|access-date=10 February 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200207062254/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-china-51409801|archive-date=7 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Graham-Harrison|first=Emma|url=https://www.theguardian.com/global-development/2020/feb/07/coronavirus-chinese-rage-death-whistleblower-doctor-li-wenliang|title='Hero who told the truth': Chinese rage over coronavirus death of whistleblower doctor|date=6 February 2020|work=The Guardian|access-date=10 February 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200207062759/https://www.theguardian.com/global-development/2020/feb/07/coronavirus-chinese-rage-death-whistleblower-doctor-li-wenliang|archive-date=7 February 2020}}</ref> His death widespread public anger in the aftermath, in what has been described as \"one of the biggest outpourings of online criticism of the government in years,\" was not a topic that was permitted for coverage.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/china/2020/02/07/li-wenliangs-death-is-a-new-crisis-for-chinas-rulers|title=Li Wenliang's death is a new crisis for China's rulers|work=The Economist|access-date=12 February 2020|issn=0013-0613}}</ref>\n\nOn 20 January, [[Communist Party of China|Chinese Communist Party]] [[General Secretary of the Communist Party of China|General Secretary]] [[Xi Jinping]] made his first public remark on the outbreak and spoke of \"the need for the timely release of information\".<ref name=\"xinhuanet138721535\">{{Cite news |url=http://xinhuanet.com/english/2020-01/20/c_138721535.htm |title=Xi orders resolute efforts to curb virus spread |date=20 January 2020 |access-date=25 January 2020 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200124174142/http://www.xinhuanet.com/english/2020-01/20/c_138721535.htm |archive-date=24 January 2020 |agency=Xinhua News Agency}}</ref> One day later, the CPC [[Central Political and Legal Affairs Commission]], the most powerful political organ in China overseeing legal enforcement and the police, wrote \"self-deception will only make the epidemic worse and turn a natural disaster that was controllable into a man-made disaster at great cost,\" and \"only openness can minimise panic to the greatest extent.\" The commission then added, \"anyone who deliberately delays and hides the reporting of cases out of self-interest will be nailed on a pillar of shame for eternity.\"<ref name=\"20200122washingtonpost\">{{Cite news |last=Fifield |first=Anna |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/asia_pacific/chinese-officials-urge-people-not-to-travel-in-and-out-of-city-at-center-of-virus-outbreak/2020/01/21/60680d3e-3c2d-11ea-afe2-090eb37b60b1_story.html |title=Chinese officials try to contain virus outbreak as first case confirmed in U.S. |date=22 January 2020 |work=[[The Washington Post]] |access-date=25 January 2020 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200124175758/https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/asia_pacific/chinese-officials-urge-people-not-to-travel-in-and-out-of-city-at-center-of-virus-outbreak/2020/01/21/60680d3e-3c2d-11ea-afe2-090eb37b60b1_story.html |archive-date=24 January 2020 |last2=Sun |first2=Lina H. |last3=Bernstein |first3=Lenny}}</ref><ref name=\"scmp3046984\">{{Cite news |last=Zheng |first=William |url=https://www.scmp.com/news/china/politics/article/3046984/china-warns-cadres-cover-spread-virus-and-be-nailed-pillar |title=China's credibility on the line as it tries to dispels fears it will cover up spread of Wuhan virus |date=21 January 2020 |work=South China Morning Post |access-date=25 January 2020 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200125014942/https://www.scmp.com/news/china/politics/article/3046984/china-warns-cadres-cover-spread-virus-and-be-nailed-pillar |archive-date=25 January 2020 |last2=Lau |first2=Mimi}}</ref> Xi Jinping later also instructed authorities \"to strengthen the guidance of public opinions\", language which some view as a call for censorship after commentators on social media became increasingly pointedly critical and angry at the government due to the epidemic.<ref name=\"WSJ\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-strains-to-stamp-out-coronavirus-criticisms-at-home-11580207403 |title=China Strains to Stamp Out Coronavirus Criticisms at Home |last=Wei |first=Lingling |date=28 January 2020 |work=[[The Wall Street Journal]] |access-date=29 January 2020 |issn=0099-9660 |url-access=subscription}}</ref>  on 30 January, [[Supreme People's Court|China's Supreme Court]], delivered a rare rebuke against the country's police forces, calling the \"unreasonably harsh crackdown on online rumours\" as undermining public trust.<ref name=\"20200130Guardian\">{{Cite news  |first1=Alison |last1=Rourke|first2= Molly |last2=Blackall |first3= Damien |last3=Gayle |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/live/2020/jan/30/coronavirus-live-updates-china-death-toll-wuhan-evacuation-foreign-nationals-citizens-latest-news |title=Virus death toll reaches 213 in China \u2013 as it happened |date=31 January 2020 |work=The Guardian |access-date=2 February 2020 |last4=Weaver |first4=Matthew |issn=0261-3077 |first5= Jessica|last5=Murray |last6=Doherty |first6=Ben |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200130002626/https://www.theguardian.com/world/live/2020/jan/30/coronavirus-live-updates-china-death-toll-wuhan-evacuation-foreign-nationals-citizens-latest-news |archive-date=30 January 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAs part of the central government's \"bifurcated approach to diffuse discontent\", citizens were permitted to criticise local officials so long as they did not \"question the basic legitimacy of the party\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/asia_pacific/in-coronavirus-outbreak-chinas-leaders-scramble-to-avert-a-chernobyl-moment/2020/01/29/bc4eb52a-4250-11ea-99c7-1dfd4241a2fe_story.html |title=In coronavirus pandemic, China's leaders scramble to avert a Chernobyl moment |website=The Washington Post |access-date=10 February 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200204085411/https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/asia_pacific/in-coronavirus-outbreak-chinas-leaders-scramble-to-avert-a-chernobyl-moment/2020/01/29/bc4eb52a-4250-11ea-99c7-1dfd4241a2fe_story.html |archive-date=4 February 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> The [[Cyberspace Administration of China|Cyberspace Administration]] (CAC) declared its intent to foster a \"good online atmosphere,\" with CAC notices sent to video platforms encouraging them to \"not to push any negative story, and not to conduct non-official livestreaming on the virus.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-health-censorship-idUSKBN2051BP|title=China's online censors tighten grip after brief coronavirus respite|date=11 February 2020|agency=Reuters|access-date=12 February 2020}}</ref> Censorship has been observed being applied on news articles and social media posts deemed to hold negative tones about the coronavirus and the governmental response, including posts mocking Xi Jinping for not visiting areas of the epidemic,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/feb/04/blame-xi-jinping-absence-coronavirus-frontline-china-crisis|title=Taking credit, avoiding blame? Xi Jinping's absence from coronavirus frontline|last=Kuo|first=Lily|date=4 February 2020|work=The Guardian|access-date=5 February 2020|issn=0261-3077|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200204231032/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/feb/04/blame-xi-jinping-absence-coronavirus-frontline-china-crisis|archive-date=4 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> an article that predicted negative effects of the epidemic on the economy, and calls to remove local government officials.<ref name=\"auto5\" /><ref name=\"auto3\" /><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/01/31/asia/wuhan-virus-china-censorship-intl-hnk/index.html|title=China is waking up to the dangers of knee-jerk censorship in a crisis|first=James|last=Griffiths|publisher=CNN|access-date=2 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200202033436/https://www.cnn.com/2020/01/31/asia/wuhan-virus-china-censorship-intl-hnk/index.html|archive-date=2 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vice.com/en_ca/article/g5xykx/you-can-now-go-to-jail-in-china-for-criticizing-beijings-coronavirus-response|title=You Can Now Go to Jail in China for Criticizing Beijing's Coronavirus Response|last=Gilbert|first=David|date=30 January 2020|website=Vice|access-date=2 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200131082945/https://www.vice.com/en_ca/article/g5xykx/you-can-now-go-to-jail-in-china-for-criticizing-beijings-coronavirus-response|archive-date=31 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>  While censorship had been briefly relaxed giving a \"window of about two weeks in which Chinese journalists were able to publish hard-hitting stories exposing the mishandling of the novel coronavirus by officials\", since then private news outlets were reportedly required to use \"planned and controlled publicity\" with the authorities' consent.<ref name=\"auto3\"/><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-health-censorship/chinas-online-censors-tighten-grip-after-brief-coronavirus-respite-idUSKBN2051BP|title=China's online censors tighten grip after brief coronavirus respite|date=11 February 2020|accessdate=22 February 2020|agency=Reuters}}</ref>\n\n==== Approval of Chinese responses ====\n[[File:President Trump Addresses a Briefing on the Coronavirus (49463760243).jpg|thumb|On 29 January, President Trump received a briefing on the coronavirus in China.]]\n\nChina's response to the virus, in comparison to the [[2003 SARS outbreak]], has been praised by some foreign leaders.<ref>{{Cite news |last=AFP |url= https://www.business-standard.com/article/pti-stories/trump-praises-china-efforts-and-transparency-on-virus-120012500107_1.html |title=Trump praises China 'efforts and transparency' on virus |date=25 January 2020 |work=Business Standard India |access-date=28 January 2020 |url-status=live |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200125151634/https://www.business-standard.com/article/pti-stories/trump-praises-china-efforts-and-transparency-on-virus-120012500107_1.html |archive-date=25 January 2020}}</ref> U.S. President Trump thanked Chinese leader Xi Jinping \"on behalf of the American People\" on 24 January on Twitter, stating that \"China has been working very hard to contain the Coronavirus. The United States greatly appreciates their efforts and transparency\" and declaring that \"It will all work out well.\"<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.straitstimes.com/world/united-states/trump-praises-china-efforts-and-transparency-on-wuhan-virus |title=Trump praises China 'efforts and transparency' on Wuhan virus |date=25 January 2020 |work=[[The Straits Times]] |url-status=live |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200127163253/https://www.straitstimes.com/world/united-states/trump-praises-china-efforts-and-transparency-on-wuhan-virus |archive-date=27 January 2020 |access-date=28 January 2020}}</ref> Germany's health minister [[Jens Spahn]], in an interview on ''[[Bloomberg Television|Bloomberg TV]]'', said with comparison to the Chinese response to SARS in 2003: \"There's a big difference to SARS. We have a much more transparent China. The action of China is much more effective in the first days already.\" He also praised the international co-operation and communication in dealing with the virus.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.dw.com/en/coronavirus-reaches-europe-as-france-confirms-3-cases/a-52145333 |title=Coronavirus reaches Europe as France confirms 3 cases |date=24 January 2020 |work=[[Deutsche Welle]] |access-date=28 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-01-24/china-doing-good-job-in-combating-virus-german-minister-says |title=China Doing Good Job in Combating Virus, German Minister Says |work=[[Bloomberg News]] |access-date=28 January 2020 |url-access=subscription}}</ref> In a letter to Xi, Singaporean president [[Halimah Yacob]] applauded China's \"swift, decisive and comprehensive measures\" in safeguarding the health of the Chinese people, while prime minister [[Lee Hsien Loong]] remarked of \"China's firm and decisive response\" in communities affected by the virus.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/covid19-coronavirus-singapore-china-solidarity-12465678 |title=Singapore leaders stand in solidarity with China over COVID-19 outbreak |work=[[Channel NewsAsia]] |access-date=24 February 2020}}</ref> Similar sentiments were expressed by Russian president [[Vladimir Putin]].<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.scmp.com/news/china/diplomacy/article/3050782/russia-and-china-pledge-maintain-special-relationship-despite |title=Russia and China pledge to maintain special relationship despite Moscow's slow response to coronavirus |work=[[South China Morning Post]] |access-date=24 February 2020 |date=16 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nAt a Sunday mass at [[St. Peter's Square]] in Vatican City on 26 January, [[Pope Francis]] praised \"the great commitment by the Chinese community that has already been put in place to combat the epidemic\" and commenced a closing prayer for \"the people who are sick because of the virus that has spread through China\".<ref>{{Cite news |url= https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-health-pope-idUSKBN1ZP0EP |title=Pope Francis praises China's efforts to contain coronavirus |date=26 January 2020 |access-date=28 January 2020 |work=[[Reuters]]}}</ref>\n\n=== India ===\n{{Main|2020 coronavirus pandemic in India|2020 India coronavirus lockdown}}\nThe Indian government airlifted 324 of its citizens from China on 31 January and 1 February via Air India special chartered flights.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://qz.com/india/1803713/air-india-pilot-recalls-wuhan-coronavirus-evacuation-mission/|title=Air India pilot recalls the \"deathly quiet\" in Wuhan amidst coronavirus evacuation|last=Sharma|first=Niharika|website=Quartz India|language=en|access-date=2020-03-09}}</ref> After Pakistan's refusal to evacuate its students from Wuhan, the Indian government offered to support them with evacuation along with citizens of other neighbouring countries.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/india-had-offered-to-evacuate-pakistani-students-from-coronavirus-hit-wuhan-jaishankar-tells-rajya-sabha-1644278-2020-02-07|title=India had offered to evacuate Pakistani students from coronavirus-hit Wuhan, Jaishankar tells Rajya Sabha|last=Delhi7 February|first=India Today Web Desk New|last2=7 February|first2=2020UPDATED|website=India Today|language=en|access-date=2020-03-09|last3=Ist|first3=2020 18:50}}</ref> On 17 February, India announced a special [[C-17 Globemaster]] flight carrying medical supplies to support China in Wuhan and evacuating citizens of India and neighbouring countries. India eventually evacuated 647 people including citizens of Maldives and Bangladesh.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Chaudhury|first=Dipanjan Roy|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/china-delaying-permission-to-india-to-send-flight-carrying-relief-materials-to-wuhan/articleshow/74252370.cms?from=mdr|title=Chinese wall stopping evacuation of Indian nationals from Wuhan|date=2020-02-22|work=The Economic Times|access-date=2020-03-09}}</ref>\n\nOn 15 March, after a video conference of [[SAARC]] leaders, PM [[Narendra Modi]] allocated [[Indian rupee|\u20b9]]74 [[crore]] (US$10 million) of funds classified as COVID-19 Emergency Fund for the SAARC countries.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.livemint.com/news/india/saarc-video-conference-live-we-evacuated-1-400-indians-from-different-countries-says-modi-11584273185030.html|title=PM Modi proposes Covid-19 emergency fund to SAARC leaders, offers $10 mn|date=2020-03-15|website=Livemint|language=en|access-date=2020-03-16}}</ref>\n\nAs a precautionary measure, India closed all of its international land borders on 16 March.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mohfw.gov.in/NewinstructionsDt14032020Restirctiononinternationalpassengertraffic.pdf|title=NewinstructionsDt14032020Restirctiononinternationalpassengertraffic.pdf|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319061749/https://www.mohfw.gov.in/NewinstructionsDt14032020Restirctiononinternationalpassengertraffic.pdf|archive-date=19 March 2020|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mohfw.gov.in/GuidelinesDT13032020.pdf|title=GuidelinesDT13032020.pdf|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323075951/https://www.mohfw.gov.in/GuidelinesDT13032020.pdf|archive-date=23 March 2020|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref> On 22 March, India locked down places where cases had been confirmed\u201482 districts in 22 states and Union Territories\u2014until 31 March,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/82-districts-under-lockdown-over-covid-19-what-s-open-and-what-is-shut/story-c1AEMZXuuXN6FvmrAdRvsJ.html|title=82 districts under lockdown over Covid-19: What is shut and where|last=|first=|date=2020-03-23|website=Hindustan Times|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=23 March 2020}}</ref> although essential services and commodities were to continue.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Jagannath|first1=J.|url=https://www.livemint.com/news/india/delhi-lockdown-to-start-at-6-am-monday-until-31-march-kejriwal-11584881955813.html|title=Delhi lockdown to start at 6 am Monday, until 31 March: Kejriwal|date=22 March 2020|work=Livemint|accessdate=22 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/kolkata/lockdown-in-west-bengal-from-5pm-today-government-to-shut-down-non-essentials/articleshow/74766599.cms|title=Lockdown in West Bengal: From 5pm today, government to shut down non-essentials|date=23 March 2020|work=The Times of India|accessdate=23 March 2020}}</ref> 80 cities including major cities such as Bengaluru, Chennai, Delhi, Mumbai, Kolkata, Nagpur, Varanasi and Raipur were also put under lockdown.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Gunasekar|first1=Arvind|url=https://www.ndtv.com/india-news/coronavirus-covid-19-80-cities-across-india-go-into-lockdown-till-march-31-what-it-means-2198894|title=Coronavirus: 80 Cities Across India Go Into Lockdown Till March 31. What It Means|date=23 March 2020|work=NDTV|accessdate=23 March 2020|last2=Bhattacharji|first2=Chetan}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Marpakwar|first1=Prafulla|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/mumbai/poor-public-response-pushed-govt-to-declare-lockdown-in-mumbai/articleshow/74766049.cms|title=Poor public response pushed govt to declare lockdown in Mumbai|date=23 March 2020|work=The Times of India|accessdate=23 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 24 March, the government announced a nationwide lockdown to be in effect for 21 days from 25 March until 14 April.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-india-52024239|title=India's 1.3bn population told to stay at home|date=2020-03-25|work=BBC News|access-date=2020-03-25|language=en-GB}}</ref> This lockdown included [[Indian Railways]], the biggest employer in India; it was the first shutdown of the trains in 167 years.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/04/05/asia/indian-railways-coronavirus-hospitals-intl-hnk/index.html|title=India has closed its railways for the first time in 167 years. Now trains are being turned into hospitals|last=Ramaprasad|first=Hema|date=6 April 2020|website=CNN|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n\n==== Criticism of Indian response ====\nThe Indian government has been condemned for alledged instances of [[police brutality]] to enforce the [[2020 India coronavirus lockdown|national lockdown]] that began on 24 March.<ref name=\"AutoDW-243\"/>\n\n=== Indonesia ===\nMany Indonesians criticised the government for a slow response and downplaying the pandemic. WHO, Australian government, and United States embassy in Indonesia have expressed their doubts about the Indonesian government's response to the pandemic.<ref>{{cite web |author1=BERITASATU |title=We Don't Cover Things Up, Indonesia Says Amid Doubts Over Its Covid-19 Handling |url=https://jakartaglobe.id/news/we-dont-cover-things-up-indonesia-says-amid-doubts-over-its-covid19-handling |website=Jakarta Globe |date=28 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe governor of [[West Sumatra]] province, [[Irwan Prayitno]] faced backlash for accepting 174 tourists from China to the province. 174 Chinese tourists from [[Kunming]] arrived at [[Minangkabau International Airport]] at [[Padang Pariaman Regency]] as [[Citilink]] adds Padang - Kunming route. Prayitno received further backlash after welcoming the group of tourists himself at the airport and giving them a \"grand welcome\" with a cultural parade. The move angered local residents who demanded the governor return the group to China.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Nasution |first1=Rahmad |title=174 Chinese tourists visit West Sumatra amid fear of coronavirus |url=https://en.antaranews.com/news/140319/174-chinese-tourists-visit-west-sumatra-amid-fear-of-coronavirus |website=Antara News |date=26 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=150 Turis China Disambut Gubernur Sumbar, Warga Protes di Medsos, Begini Penjelasannya |url=https://bali.tribunnews.com/2020/01/28/150-turis-china-disambut-gubernur-sumbar-warga-protes-di-medsos-begini-penjelasannya |website=Tribun Bali |language=id-ID |date=28 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nHealth experts are concerned that the country is failing to identify the transmission of the virus.<ref name=\"JakPost 20200229\">{{cite web | url=https://www.thejakartapost.com/academia/2020/02/29/lets-not-kid-ourselves-indonesia-is-unlikely-to-be-covid-19-free-and-thats-not-our-biggest-problem.html | title=Let's not kid ourselves. Indonesia is unlikely to be COVID-19-free. And that's not our biggest problem. | work=The Jakarta Post | date=29 February 2020 | accessdate=29 February 2020 | last=Hermawan | first=Ary}}</ref> [[Marc Lipsitch]], professor of [[epidemiology]] at the [[Harvard T. H. Chan School of Public Health]], \"analysed air traffic out of the Chinese city at the centre of the outbreak in China and suggested in a report ... that Indonesia might have missed cases\" of coronavirus.<ref>{{cite news|accessdate=8 April 2020 |first1=Karen|last1=McVeigh|first2=Emma|last2=Graham-Harrison |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/feb/14/indonesia-coronavirus-academic-harvard-marc-lipsitch |title=Academic stands by research querying Indonesia's claim to be coronavirus-free |date=14 February 2020 |newspaper=The Guardian |issn=0261-3077}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/02/reported-cases-coronavirus-indonesia-200218112232304.html | title=Why are there no reported cases of coronavirus in Indonesia? | accessdate=2 March 2020 | website=aljazeera.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2020/02/19/indonesia-coronavirus-screening-may-miss-virus-carriers/ | title=Indonesian Screening May Be Missing Virus Carriers | accessdate=2 March 2020 | last=Firdaus | first=Febriana}}</ref> Western diplomats<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.merdeka.com/dunia/kekhawatiran-as-dan-negara-barat-soal-penanganan-corona-di-indonesia.html | title=Kekhawatiran AS dan Negara Barat Soal Penanganan Corona di Indonesia | work=Merdeka.com | date=28 February 2020 | accessdate=29 February 2020 | last=Pandasurya | first=Wijaya | language=id}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://nasional.kontan.co.id/news/kedutaan-besar-negara-barat-cemas-dengan-penanganan-virus-corona-di-Indonesia | title=Kedutaan besar negara Barat cemas dengan penanganan virus corona di Indonesia | work=Kontan | date=27 February 2020 | accessdate=29 February 2020 | editor=S.S. Kurniawan | language=id}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.kompas.com/tren/read/2020/03/01/090000165/nol-kasus-perdana-menteri-australia-ragukan-penanganan-virus-corona-di | title=Nol Kasus, Perdana Menteri Australia Ragukan Penanganan Virus Corona di Indonesia | work=Kompas.com | date=1 March 2020 | accessdate=2 March 2020 | author=Nur Rohmi Aida | language=id}}</ref> as well as local<ref name=\"JakPost 20200229\"/><ref>{{cite web | url=https://jakartaglobe.id/news/we-dont-cover-things-up-indonesia-says-amid-doubts-over-its-covid19-handling | title=We Don't Cover Things Up, Indonesia Says Amid Doubts Over Its Covid-19 Handling | work=Jakarta Globe | date=28 February 2020 | accessdate=29 February 2020}}</ref> and international<ref>{{cite web | url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2020/02/19/indonesia-coronavirus-screening-may-miss-virus-carriers/ | title=Indonesian Screening May Be Missing Virus Carriers | work=Foreign Policy | date=19 February 2020 | accessdate=29 February 2020 | last=Firdaus | first=Febriana}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://time.com/5792180/southeast-asia-undetected-coronavirus/ | title=A Silent Epidemic? Experts Fear the Coronavirus Is Spreading Undetected in Southeast Asia | work=Time (magazine) | date=28 February 2020 | accessdate=29 February 2020 | last=Barron | first=Laignee}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | first1=Randy | last1=Mulyanto | url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/02/reported-cases-coronavirus-indonesia-200218112232304.html | title=Why are there no reported cases of coronavirus in Indonesia? | work=Al Jazeera | date=18 February 2020 | accessdate=29 February 2020 | last2=Firdaus | first2=Febriana}}</ref> news outlets postulated that the lack of cases within Indonesia result from inadequate testing and under reporting, as opposed to sheer luck and [[Divine providence|divine intervention]].<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.scmp.com/week-asia/health-environment/article/3051068/we-owe-it-god-indonesia-prays-how-it-keeping | title='We owe it to God': as Indonesia prays, how is it keeping the coronavirus at bay? | work=South China Morning Post | date=18 February 2020 | accessdate=29 February 2020 | last=Cochrane | first=Joe}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-health-indonesia/indonesia-says-lack-of-coronavirus-cases-a-blessing-from-god-idUSKCN20L1DL | title=Indonesia says lack of COVID-19 cases a blessing from God | work=Reuters | date=27 February 2020 | accessdate=29 February 2020 | last=Da Costa | first=Agustinus Beo}}</ref>\n\nThe government faced a backlash after instead pledging to set aside [[Rupiah|IDR]] 72 billion ($5m) to pay for social media influencers to attract tourists to Indonesia.<ref>{{cite news |title='Rp 72 Miliar Untuk Influencer': Cara Indonesia Merespon Virus Corona |trans-title='Rp 72 Billion for Influencers': How Indonesia Responds to the Coronavirus|url=https://www.tempo.co/abc/5348/rp-72-miliar-untuk-influencer-cara-indonesia-merespon-virus-corona |accessdate=4 March 2020 |work=Tempo |date=28 February 2020 |language=id}}</ref>\n\nIndonesian president Joko Widodo has been criticised by the Indonesian Chamber of Commerce and Industry,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://katadata.co.id/berita/2020/03/03/cegah-kepanikan-pengusaha-minta-pemerintah-jujur-soal-virus-corona|title=Cegah Kepanikan, Pengusaha Minta Pemerintah Jujur Soal Virus Corona - Katadata.co.id|date=3 March 2020|website=katadata.co.id|language=id|access-date=14 March 2020}}</ref> human rights groups,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nasional.tempo.co/read/1319111/komnas-ham-minta-pemerintah-terbuka-soal-virus-corona|title=Komnas HAM Minta Pemerintah Terbuka Soal Virus Corona|last=Persada|first=Syailendra|date=13 March 2020|website=Tempo|language=en|access-date=14 March 2020}}</ref> and by political parties including [[Golkar]] and [[Prosperous Justice Party|Partai Keadilan Sejahtera]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnnindonesia.com/nasional/20200313070528-20-483043/pks-minta-pemerintah-lebih-terbuka-soal-corona|title=PKS Minta Pemerintah Lebih Terbuka soal Corona|website=nasional|language=id-ID|access-date=14 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.detik.com/berita/d-4937624/daerah-sumber-corona-harus-diungkap-golkar-dorong-pemerintah-transparan|title=Daerah Sumber Corona Harus Diungkap, Golkar Dorong Pemerintah Transparan|last=Zhacky|first=Mochamad|website=detiknews|language=id-ID|access-date=14 March 2020}}</ref> for a lack of transparency regarding the information on COVID-19. Widodo has insisted not to share with the travel history details of patients tested positive with coronavirus in an attempt to reduce panic and uneasiness in the general public.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nasional.kompas.com/read/2020/03/13/16163481/jokowi-akui-pemerintah-rahasiakan-sejumlah-informasi-soal-corona|title=Jokowi Akui Pemerintah Rahasiakan Sejumlah Informasi soal Corona|last=Media|first=Kompas Cyber|website=KOMPAS.com|language=id|access-date=14 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Iran ===\n{{Main|2020 coronavirus pandemic in Iran}}\n[[File:Disinfection of Tehran subway wagons against coronavirus 2020-02-26 09.jpg|thumb|Disinfection of [[Tehran Metro|Tehran subway]] wagons against coronavirus]]\nIran reported its first confirmed cases of SARS-CoV-2 infections on 19 February 2020 in [[Qom]], where according to the [[Ministry of Health and Medical Education]], both had died later that day.<ref>{{cite web |title=Coronavirus Arrives in Iran: Two People Test Positive in Qom |url=http://irangov.ir/detail/334964 |website=irangov.ir |date= 19 February 2020 |accessdate=6 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Iran Confirms 3 New Coronavirus Cases |url=http://irangov.ir/detail/335028 |website=irangov.ir |date= 20 February 2020 |accessdate=6 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nEarly measures announced by the government included the cancellation of concerts and other cultural events,<ref>{{cite web|url= https://en.radiofarda.com/a/iranian-doctors-call-for-long-holiday-to-contain-coronavirus-outbreak/30449047.html |title=Iranian Doctors Call For 'Long Holiday' To Contain Coronavirus, As Sixth Victim Dies |website=Radio Farda |publisher=Radio Free Europe/Radio Liberty |date=22 February 2020 |accessdate=8 March 2020}}</ref> sporting events,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.varzesh3.com/news/1669982/\u0644\u063a\u0648-\u0647\u0645\u0647-\u0645\u0633\u0627\u0628\u0642\u0627\u062a-\u0648\u0631\u0632\u0634\u06cc-\u0628\u0647-\u0645\u062f\u062a-\u0631\u0648\u0632|title=\u0644\u063a\u0648 \u0647\u0645\u0647 \u0645\u0633\u0627\u0628\u0642\u0627\u062a \u0648\u0631\u0632\u0634\u06cc \u0628\u0647 \u0645\u062f\u062a \u06f1\u06f0 \u0631\u0648\u0632|website=varzesh3.com|language=Persian|access-date=23 February 2020}}</ref> and Friday prayers,<ref>{{cite news|last=Gambrell|first=Jon|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/middle_east/saudi-arabia-halts-travel-to-islams-holiest-site-over-virus%2f2020%2f02%2f26%2fc86ec712-5918-11ea-8efd-0f904bdd8057_story.html|title=Iran news agencies report Friday prayers canceled in Tehran|agency=Associated Press|work=The Washington Post}}</ref> closure of universities, higher education institutions and schools,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://en.radiofarda.com/a/iran-announces-closure-of-universities-schools-to-fight-coronavirus/30449711.html|title=Iran Announces Closure Of Universities, Schools As Coronavirus Death Toll Rises|website=Radio Farda|publisher=Radio Free Europe/Radio Liberty|date=2020-02-23|accessdate=2020-03-08}}</ref> and allocated 5&nbsp;trillion rials to combat the virus.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.jamaran.news/\u0628\u062e\u0634-\u067e\u0631\u0648\u0641\u0627\u06cc\u0644-182/1363201-\u0627\u062e\u062a\u0635\u0627\u0635-\u0645\u06cc\u0644\u06cc\u0627\u0631\u062f-\u062a\u0648\u0645\u0627\u0646-\u0628\u0647-\u0648\u0632\u0627\u0631\u062a-\u0628\u0647\u062f\u0627\u0634\u062a-\u0628\u0631\u0627\u06cc-\u0645\u0642\u0627\u0628\u0644\u0647-\u0628\u0627-\u06a9\u0631\u0648\u0646\u0627|title=\u0627\u062e\u062a\u0635\u0627\u0635 530 \u0645\u06cc\u0644\u06cc\u0627\u0631\u062f \u062a\u0648\u0645\u0627\u0646 \u0628\u0647 \u0648\u0632\u0627\u0631\u062a \u0628\u0647\u062f\u0627\u0634\u062a \u0628\u0631\u0627\u06cc \u0645\u0642\u0627\u0628\u0644\u0647 \u0628\u0627 \u06a9\u0631\u0648\u0646\u0627|website=\u067e\u0627\u06cc\u06af\u0627\u0647 \u062e\u0628\u0631\u06cc \u062c\u0645\u0627\u0631\u0627\u0646 \u2013 \u0627\u0645\u0627\u0645 \u062e\u0645\u06cc\u0646\u06cc \u2013 \u0627\u0646\u0642\u0644\u0627\u0628 \u0627\u0633\u0644\u0627\u0645\u06cc|language=fa|access-date=23 February 2020}}</ref>  President [[Hassan Rouhani]]  said on 26 February 2020 that there were no plans to quarantine areas affected by the outbreak, and only individuals would be quarantined.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-middle-east-51651454|title=Coronavirus: Iran has no plans to quarantine cities, Rouhani says|date=26 February 2020|publisher=BBC}}</ref> However, [[Shia]] shrines in Qom remained open to pilgrims.<ref>{{cite news|author1=Ramin Mostaghim |author2=Mostafa Salem |author3=Tamara Qiblawi|url=https://edition.cnn.com/2020/02/26/middleeast/iran-coronavirus-intl/index.html|title=Iran was already struggling with one crisis. Now it has the worst coronavirus pandemic in the Middle East|date=26 February 2020|publisher=CNN}}</ref>\n\nIran became a center of the spread of the virus after China.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/24/world/middleeast/coronavirus-iran.html |title='Recipe for a Massive Viral Outbreak': Iran Emerges as a Worldwide Threat |date=24 February 2020|work=The New York Times |authors= David D. Kirkpatrick, Farnaz Fassihi and Mujib Mashal  }}</ref><ref name=newyorker /> Amidst claims of a cover-up of the extent of the outbreak in the country,<ref>{{cite news|authors=Sam Jones, Aamna Mohdin and agencies|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/feb/24/coronavirus-dead-in-iranian-city-of-qom|title=Coronavirus: Iran denies cover-up as six deaths reported in Italy|work=The Guardian|date=24 February 2020}}</ref> over ten countries have traced their cases back to Iran, indicating that the extent of the outbreak may be more severe than that admitted by the Iranian government.<ref name=newyorker>{{cite web|url=https://www.newyorker.com/news/our-columnists/how-iran-became-a-new-epicenter-of-the-coronavirus-outbreak|title=How Iran Became A New Epicenter of the coronavirus pandemic|last1=Wright|first1=Robin |date=24 February 2020 |work=The New Yorker}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Coronavirus pummels Iran leadership as data show spread is far worse than reported|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/middle_east/coronavirus-pummels-iran-leadership-as-data-show-spread-is-far-worse-than-reported/2020/03/04/7b1196ae-5c9f-11ea-ac50-18701e14e06d_story.html|newspaper=The Washington Post|date=4 March 2020|authors=Erin Cunningham & Dalton Bennett }}</ref> The [[Islamic Consultative Assembly|Iranian Parliament]] was shut down, with 23 of the 290 members of parliament reported to have had tested positive for the virus on 3 March.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/8-percent-iran-parliament-has-coronavirus-it-released-54000-prisoners-2020-3|title=8% of Iran's parliament has the coronavirus, and it released 54,000 prisoners as the country descends into chaos|last=Haltiwanger|first=John|website=Business Insider|access-date=4 March 2020}}</ref> A number of senior government officials as well as two members of parliament have died from the disease.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-middle-east-51801968 |title=Virus hits highest levels of Iran's government |author= Tse Yin Lee |date=9 March 2020 |work=BBC}}</ref>\n\n==== Criticism of Iranian response ====\n[[File:13981205000415637181505100958241 \u0646\u0634\u0633\u062a \u062e\u0628\u0631\u06cc \u0633\u062e\u0646\u06af\u0648\u06cc \u062f\u0648\u0644\u062a.jpg|thumb|Deputy Health Minister [[Iraj Harirchi]] (left) at a press conference after which he tested positive for the virus.]]\nIranians criticized government authorities for proceeding with [[2020 Iranian legislative election|elections]] while the disease was spreading and closing secular spaces while keeping shrines open, especially in the Shia holy city of [[Qom]].<ref name=\"veconomist\" >{{cite news|title= The Iranian regime risks exacerbating the outbreak of covid-19|url= https://www.economist.com/middle-east-and-africa/2020/02/24/the-iranian-regime-risks-exacerbating-the-outbreak-of-covid-19|work=[[The Economist]]|date=24 February 2020}}</ref> Asif Shuja of the National University of Singapore's Middle East Institute suggested that \"the fact that Iran reported deaths on the same day as its first infections right before its parliamentary elections 'can compel anyone' that there has been a cover-up\".<ref name=\"auto4\">{{cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/03/02/irans-coronavirus-updates-cannot-entirely-be-trusted-expert-says.html|title=Iran's coronavirus updates cannot 'entirely' be trusted, expert says|website=cnbc|access-date=2 March 2020}}</ref> Scrutiny has also been targeted at the government's unwillingness to implement area-wide quarantine measures like those implemented by China and Italy, with Iranian officials calling quarantines \"old-fashioned.\"<ref name=\"AutoDW-236\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-51628484|title=Top Iran health official gets virus as fears grow|date=25 February 2020|publisher=BBC News|access-date=25 February 2020}}</ref> There have been concerns that the Iranian government's official counts were an underestimate.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/02/27/who-says-coronavirus-entered-iran-unseen-and-undetected-warns-outbreak-could-be-even-worse.html|title=WHO says coronavirus entered Iran 'undetected,' warns outbreak could be worse than is known|last=Feuer|first=William| name-list-format = vanc |date=27 February 2020|publisher=CNBC|access-date=28 February 2020}}</ref> The WHO's director-general, Tedros Adhanom Ghebreyesus, said that \"the WHO has its \"own mechanism\" for checking facts and has not seen problems with Iran's reported figures\".<ref name=\"auto4\"/>\n\n=== Japan ===\n{{main|2020 coronavirus pandemic in Japan}}\n{{Expand section|date=April 2020}}\nOn 27 February 2020, Prime Minister [[Shinzo Abe]] requested that all Japanese elementary, junior high, and high schools close until early April to help contain the virus.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://english.kyodonews.net/news/2020/02/c3c57bbce11d-breaking-news-govt-will-ask-all-schools-in-japan-to-shut-for-virus-fears-abe.html|title=PM Abe asks all schools in Japan to temporarily close over coronavirus|first=KYODO|last=NEWS|website=Kyodo News+}}</ref>\n\nThe outbreak has been a concern for the [[2020 Summer Olympics]] which is scheduled to take place in Tokyo starting at the end of July.<ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus: Tokyo 2020 could be postponed to end of year \u2013 Japan's Olympic minister |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/olympics/51717839 |publisher=BBC News |date=3 March 2020}}</ref> The Japanese government has thus been taking extra precautions to help minimise the outbreak's impact.<ref name=\"olympicstokyo\">{{cite news |title=Coronavirus could see the Tokyo Olympics cancelled. Is Japan's handling of the outbreak to blame? |url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2020-03-03/coronavirus-will-the-diamond-princess-sink-japans-olympics-dream/12015202 |publisher=ABC News |date=3 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==== Criticism of Japanese response ====\nDiplomatic [[Japan\u2013South Korea relations|relations between Japan and South Korea]] worsened, as South Korea criticized Japan's \"ambiguous and passive quarantine efforts\".<ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus quarantine plans ignite row between South Korea and Japan |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/06/coronavirus-quarantine-plans-ignite-row-between-south-korea-and-japan |work=The Guardian |date=6 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Japan and Korea Won't Let A Pandemic Stop Them Fighting |url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2020/03/12/japan-and-korea-wont-let-a-pandemic-stop-them-fighting/ |work=[[Foreign Policy]] |date=12 March 2020}}</ref> Under the post-war constitution, Japanese people are guaranteed a significant amount of freedoms and individual rights, hence the government does not have powers that can restrict movement in the same manner that Italy and the People's Republic of China can. The government does not have the power to quarantine domestic patients or impose curfews.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/2020/02/05/national/japan-lawmakers-coronavirus-crisis-state-of-emergency-clause-rights/|title=Lawmakers slammed for using coronavirus to justify emergency clause for Japan's Constitution, curbing rights|date=5 February 2020|work=Japan Times|access-date=1 March 2020|issn=0447-5763}}</ref>\n\nJapan's [[Ministry of Health, Labour and Welfare|Ministry of Health, Labor and Welfare]] has been criticized for a perceived delayed response. Critics have observed that while Japan announced the first case of infection on 28 January, it took until 17 February for the Health Ministry to inform the public on how to reach public screening centers and 25 February, for the government to issue a \"basic policy\" on outbreak response. The overdue response times of the government has led critics to accuse Abe of \"callous indifference in the face of an unfolding disaster\" and the government as a whole as being \"out of touch with the lives of ordinary people that they seem genuinely uninterested in their plight\".<ref name=\"AutoDW-224\" /><ref name=\"AutoDW-225\" />\n\nThe strict constraints on testing for the virus by Japanese health authorities have drawn accusations from critics such as Masahiro Kami, a [[Hematology|hematologist]] and director of the Medical Governance Research Institute, towards Abe of wanting to \"downplay the number of infections or patients because of the upcoming Olympics.\" Reports that only a small select number of public health facilities were authorized to test for the virus, after which the results could only be processed by five government-approved companies, has created a bottleneck where clinics have been forced to turn away even patients who had high fevers. This has led some experts to question Japan's official case numbers, with Tobias Harris, of [[Teneo]] Intelligence in Washington, D.C. stating \"You wonder, if they were testing nearly as much as South Korea is testing, what would the actual number be? How many cases are lurking and just aren't being caught?\"<ref name=\"NYT-20FEB29-TestConstraints\">{{Cite news|last=Dooley|first=Ben |last2=Rich|first2=Motoko|last3=Inoue|first3=Makiko | name-list-format = vanc |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/29/world/asia/japan-elderly-coronavirus.html|title=In Graying Japan, Many Are Vulnerable but Few Are Being Tested|date=29 February 2020|work=The New York Times|access-date=29 February 2020|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-02-29/japan-s-abe-plans-second-virus-package-of-270-billion-yen|title=Japan's Abe Seeks to Defuse Virus Criticism With Cash, Testing|publisher=Bloomberg L.P.|url-status=live|access-date=29 February 2020|url-access=subscription}}</ref>\n\nThe quarantine measures on the cruise ship ''[[Diamond Princess (ship)|Diamond Princess]]'' has also been criticised after the ship proved a fertile breeding ground for the virus.<ref name=\"AutoDW-226\"/><ref name=\"AutoDW-227\"/> Kentaro Iwata, an infectious disease professor at Kobe University Hospital, said that the condition aboard was \"completely chaotic\" and \"violating all infection control principles\".<ref name=\"AutoDW-228\"/> A preliminary report by Japan's National Institute of Infectious Diseases (NIID) estimated that most of the transmission on the ship had occurred before the quarantine, based on the first 184 cases.<ref name=\"tjt20-1\"/> On 22 February, the Health Ministry admitted that 23 passengers were disembarked without being properly tested for the virus.<ref name=\"AutoDW-229\"/> On 23 February, a Japanese woman who tested negative before disembarking from the cruise ship later tested positive after returning to her home in [[Tochigi Prefecture]].<ref name=\"AutoDW-230\"/> She was not among the 23 passengers.<ref name=\"AutoDW-231\"/>\n\n=== Philippines ===\n{{Main|2020 coronavirus pandemic in the Philippines}}\n\nThe first COVID-19 death outside China occurred in the Philippines on 1 February.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/02/02/20/ph-records-first-death-due-to-new-coronavirus|title=First novel coronavirus death outside China recorded in PH \u2013 WHO official|date=3 February 2020|work=ABS-CBN News|access-date=10 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 9 March 2020, [[Rodrigo Duterte|President Rodrigo R. Duterte]] suspended classes in all levels in Metro Manila from 10 to 15 March.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.rappler.com/nation/253913-new-confirmed-novel-coronavirus-cases-march-9-2020|title=Duterte announces 4 more novel coronavirus cases in PH|date=9 February 2020|work=Rappler|access-date=10 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The class suspension in Metro Manila was extended to 12 April, following the decision of concerned authorities to raise the COVID-19 alert level in the country to Code Red Sublevel 2. Work in the executive branch of the government was also suspended for the same period as part of the Stringent Social Distancing Measures in the National Capital Region (NCR),<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://pia.gov.ph/press-releases/releases/1036193|title=Statement of Presidential Spokesperson Salvador Panelo on Code Red Sublevel 2|date=12 March 2020|work=Philippine Information Agency|access-date=13 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> with the directive for the concerned government agencies to form skeletal forces to ensure the delivery of basic services. Congress and the Judiciary were encouraged to do the same. Agencies providing law enforcement services, health services, and emergency services were enjoined to continue to operate at full capacity.\n\nOther salient directives, contained in a resolution adopted by the Inter-Agency Task Force on the Emerging Infectious Diseases (IATF-EID) and announced by the Philippine President on 12 March, at the Heroes Hall in [[Malaca\u00f1ang Palace|Malaca\u00f1an Palace]],<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://pia.gov.ph/news/articles/1036195|title=PRRD orders 'stringent social distancing measures' in NCR|date=12 March 2020|work=Philippine Information Agency|access-date=13 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> included, the prohibition of mass gatherings that could strain the resources of the host community, imposition of community quarantine over [[Metro Manila]], and encouragement of flexible work arrangements for the private sector among others.\n\nA memorandum containing the guidelines for stringent social distancing measures and the management of COVID-19 in the National Capital Region<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.officialgazette.gov.ph/2020/03/13/memorandum-from-the-executive-secretary-on-stringent-social-distancing-measures-and-further-guidelines-for-the-management-of-the-coronavirus-disease-2019-covid-19-situation/|title=Memorandum from the Executive Secretary On Stringent Social Distancing Measures and Further Guidelines for the Management of the Coronavirus Disease 2019 (Covid-19) Situation|date=13 March 2020|work=Official Gazette GOV.PH|access-date=15 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> was issued by Executive Secretary [[Salvador Medialdea]] by order of the president on 13 March. Among the directives embodied in the memorandum were suspension of classes and all school activities until 14 April, prohibition of mass gatherings, imposition of strict social distancing during essential meetings and religious activities, and provisions for alternative and/or flexible work arrangements.\n\nOn 16 March, the president signed Proclamation No. 929<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.officialgazette.gov.ph/2020/03/16/proclamation-no-929-s-2020/|title=Proclamation No. 929 s. 2020 Declaring a State of Calamity Throughout the Philippines due to Corona Virus Disease 2019|date=17 March 2020|publisher=Official Gazette GOV.PH|access-date=17 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> declaring a state of calamity throughout the country for a period of six months, bringing into effect the price control of basic needs and commodities, granting of interest-free loans, distribution of calamity funds and hazard allowance for public health workers and government personnel in the fields of science and technology.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.officialgazette.gov.ph/laginghanda/dagling-paliwanag-ano-ang-state-of-calamity/|title=Dagling Paliwanag: Ano ang State of Calamity?|publisher=Official Gazette GOV.PH|access-date=17 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nPresident Duterte also placed the island of [[Luzon]] under \"enhanced\" community quarantine on 16 March<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.facebook.com/CNNPhilippines/videos/cnn-philippines-special-coverage-president-rodrigo-duterte-orders-enhanced-commu/515691529377942/|title=CNN PHILIPPINES SPECIAL COVERAGE: President Rodrigo Duterte orders \u2018enhanced community quarantine\u2019 in Luzon|date=16 March 2020|publisher=CNN Philippines|work=Facebook|access-date=17 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> that further restricted the movement of people through the suspension of mass public transport and the closure of non-essential establishments. Business Process Outsourcing and export-oriented businesses were allowed to continue operation subject to certain conditions. Relevant government agencies were ordered to provide social amelioration measures.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.officialgazette.gov.ph/2020/03/16/memorandum-from-the-executive-secretary-on-community-quarantine-over-the-entire-luzon-and-further-guidelines-for-the-management-of-the-coronavirus-disease-2019-covid-19-situation/|title=Memorandum from the Executive Secretary On Community Quarantine Over the Entire Luzon and Further Guidelines for the Management of the Coronavirus Disease 2019 (COVID-19) Situation|date=16 March 2020|work=Official Gazette GOV.PH|access-date=17 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Following the sharp increase of confirmed cases, President Duterte called Congress to a special session to \"authorize the President to exercise powers necessary to carry out urgent measures to meet the current national emergency related to the Coronavirus Disease (Covid-19).\u201d<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.pna.gov.ph/articles/1097429|title=Duterte seeks \u2018more powers,\u2019 urgent measures vs. Covid-19|date=22 March 2020|publisher=Philippine News Agency|access-date=23 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== South Korea ===\n{{Main|2020 coronavirus pandemic in South Korea}}\nThe first confirmed case of the coronavirus was identified with a 35-year-old Chinese woman on 20 January. The first South Korean national to be infected occurred three days later was a 55-year-old man who worked in Wuhan and returned for a checkup with flu symptoms. The two infection reports were publicly released on 24 January. The sixth patient was the first case in South Korea who had never visited Wuhan. The 56-year-old man caught the virus when visiting a restaurant with the third patient.{{citation needed|date=March 2020}}\n[[File:Coronavirus Jongno 1.jpg|thumb|Coronavirus infection prevention tips banner in Seoul, South Korea]]\nA woman, who had returned from [[Thailand]] after a five-day vacation, was tested positive and confirmed as the sixteenth case on 4 February.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/asia/east-asia/coronavirus-south-korean-woman-travelling-home-from-thailand-tests-positive-for-virus|title=Coronavirus: South Korean woman travelling home from Thailand tests positive for virus|date=4 February 2020|website=The Straits Times|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200204092646/https://www.straitstimes.com/asia/east-asia/coronavirus-south-korean-woman-travelling-home-from-thailand-tests-positive-for-virus|archive-date=4 February 2020|accessdate=4 February 2020}}</ref> Three more cases were confirmed on 5 February, bringing the total case count to 19. The seventeenth and nineteenth patients had attended a conference in Singapore and been in contact with an infected person there.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://yna.kr/AEN20200205002356320|title=3 More Virus Cases Bring S. Korea's Total to 19, Two Confirmed after Trip to Singapore|date=5 February 2020|website=Yonhap|url-status=live|accessdate=5 February 2020}}</ref> The very same day the [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention Korea]] (KCDC) announced that the second patient had been released from hospital after being tested negative in consecutive tests, becoming the country's first coronavirus patient to fully recover.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://en.yna.co.kr/view/AEN20200205006252320|title=S. Korea Releases First Fully Recovered Coronavirus Patient from Hospital|date=5 February 2020|agency=Yonhap News Agency|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200205133506/https://en.yna.co.kr/view/AEN20200205006252320|archive-date=5 February 2020|access-date=5 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 19 February, the number of confirmed cases increased by 20. On 20 February 70 new cases were confirmed,<ref name=\"ThomReut_SKorea_zombie\">{{cite news|last1=Shin|first1=Hyonhee|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-health-southkorea-cases/like-a-zombie-apocalypse-residents-on-edge-as-coronavirus-cases-surge-in-south-korea-idUSKBN20E04F|title='Like a zombie apocalypse': Residents on edge as coronavirus cases surge in South Korea|date=20 February 2020|accessdate=20 February 2020|url-status=live <!-- live|dead|unfit|usurped -->|archiveurl=https://archive.today/D1K5i|archivedate=20 February 2020|agency=[[Thomson Reuters]]|last2=Cha|first2=Sangmi|trans-title=<!-- trans-title is the English translation -->|url-access=<!-- (subscription/registration/limited) default=free -->}}</ref> giving a total of 104 confirmed cases, according to the KCDC. According to ''[[Reuters]]'', KCDC attributed the sudden jump to 70 cases linked to \"Patient No. 31\", who had participated in a gathering in [[Daegu]] at the [[Shincheonji Church of Jesus the Temple of the Tabernacle of the Testimony]].<ref name=\"ThomReut_SKorea_zombie\" />\n\nOn 20 February, the streets of Daegu were empty in reaction to the Shincheonji outbreak. A resident described the reaction, stating \"It's like someone dropped a bomb in the middle of the city. It looks like a zombie apocalypse.\"<ref name=\"ThomReut_SKorea_zombie\" /> The first death was reported<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/health/health-news/south-korea-reports-first-coronavirus-death-infections-linked-church-rise-n1139821|title=South Korea reports first coronavirus death as infections linked to church rise|publisher=NBC News|access-date=21 February 2020}}</ref> in a mental ward of Cheongdo Daenam Hospital in [[Cheongdo County]]. According to the mayor of Daegu, the number of suspected cases as of 21 February was 544 among 4,400 examined followers of the church.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.chosun.com/site/data/html_dir/2020/02/21/2020022101558.html|title=\uc2e0\ucc9c\uc9c0 \uad00\ub828 \ud655\uc9c4\uc790 76\uba85\uc73c\ub85c \ub298\uc5b4...\ub300\uad6c \uad50\uc778 \uc758\uc2ec\uc790\ub9cc 544\uba85|language=ko|trans-title=The number of Shincheonji related doctors will increase to 74 ... Daegu members only 544|date=21 February 2020|publisher=Chosun.com}}</ref> The hospital was suspected as the source of the present outbreak after it was visited by a woman who became the second fatal case of Korea on that day. The infection spread outside via a funeral ceremony attended by members of the church.<ref name=\"b82186\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-51582186|title=South Korea virus 'emergency' as cases increase|date=21 February 2020|publisher=BBC News}}</ref><ref name=\"koreabiomed\">{{cite news|last1=Lee|first1=Han-soo|url=http://www.koreabiomed.com/news/articleView.html?idxno=7489|title=COVID-19 patients soar to 204 in Korea|date=21 February 2020|work=Korea Biomedical Review|accessdate=21 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nAll South Korean military bases were on lockdown after tests confirmed that three soldiers were indeed positive for the virus.<ref name=\"b82186\" /> Airlines cut connections and cultural schedules were being cancelled due to fears of further spread.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=20200221000249|title=Airlines to suspend more flights over coronavirus|date=21 February 2020|work=The Korea Herald|accessdate=21 February 2020|agency=Yonhap}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Song|first1=Seung-hyun|url=http://www.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=20200221000554|title=Foreign artists delay concerts in Korea due to spread of COVID-19|date=21 February 2020|work=The Korea Herald|accessdate=21 February 2020}}</ref> [[United States Forces Korea]] raised the alert level from low to moderate and cut off non-essential travel to and from USFK Daegu.<ref name=\"MT\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.militarytimes.com/news/your-military/2020/02/19/us-forces-korea-imposes-new-coronavirus-protections-after-uptick-in-s-korea-cases/|title=US Forces Korea imposes new coronavirus protections after uptick in S Korea cases|date=19 February 2020}}</ref> USFK Daegu's school facilities were closed and non-essential personnel were ordered to stay at home while any visitors going there were not allowed to enter.<ref name=\"MT\" /> USFK announced that the widow of a retired soldier who was in Daegu was diagnosed to be positive for the virus on 24 February.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stripes.com/news/pacific/usfk-dependent-tests-positive-for-coronavirus-putting-military-on-high-alert-in-south-korea-1.620023|title=USFK dependent tests positive for coronavirus, putting military on high alert in South Korea|website=Stars and Stripes}}</ref> [[Camp Humphreys]] enacted virus detection protocols, including temperature checks and raised the alert level to high.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/us-forces-korea-high-alert-for-coronavirus-after-positive-test-2020-2|title=US troops in Korea are on high alert for coronavirus after widow of retired soldier tests positive|first=David|last=Roza|website=Business Insider}}</ref> On 26 February, an American soldier based at Camp Carroll was diagnosed to be positive and was quarantined away from bases via off-base housing unit<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-health-southkorea/us-soldier-infected-as-south-korea-coronavirus-cases-rise-above-1260-idUSKCN20K045|title=U.S. Soldier infected as South Korea coronavirus cases rise above 1,260|date=26 February 2020|agency=Reuters}}</ref> with contact tracing done that showed his movements to Camp Walker.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.marketwatch.com/story/south-korea-coronavirus-cases-continue-to-soar-towns-sealed-off-in-northern-italy-2020-02-25|title=First U.S. soldier in South Korea tests positive for coronavirus; towns sealed off in northern Italy|first=Associated|last=Press|website=MarketWatch}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Incheon 2.jpg|thumb|The near-empty arrival hall of [[Incheon International Airport|Seoul\u2013Incheon International Airport]] in South Korea on 6&nbsp;March]]\n\nAs of 22 February, among 9,336 followers of the church, 1,261 reported symptoms.<ref>{{Cite web|url= http://www.mohw.go.kr/react/al/sal0301vw.jsp?PAR_MENU_ID=04&MENU_ID=0403&page=1&CONT_SEQ=353047&SEARCHKEY=TITLE&SEARCHVALUE=\ucf54\ub85c\ub098\ubc14\uc774\ub7ec |title=\ucf54\ub85c\ub098\ubc14\uc774\ub7ec\uc2a4\uac10\uc5fc\uc99d-19 \uad6d\ub0b4 \ubc1c\uc0dd \ud604\ud669 (2\uc6d4 22\uc77c 09\uc2dc) |date=22 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> At the time, 169 confirmed cases involved the church and another 111 came from the Cheongdo Daenam Hospital.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cdc.go.kr/|title=\uc9c8\ubcd1\uad00\ub9ac\ubcf8\ubd80|website=Centers for Disease Control and Prevention Korea}}</ref> 23 February saw another 123 cases with 75 being from Shincheonji<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cdc.go.kr/board/board.es?mid=a30402000000&bid=0030&act=view&list_no=366303&tag=&nPage=1|title=123 additional cases have been confirmed|author=<!--Not stated-->|date=23 February 2020|website=[[Korea Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]]|access-date=24 February 2020}}</ref> and 24 February saw 161 additional cases with 129 being from the religious group. Over 27,000 people have been tested for the virus with 19,127 negative results.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cdc.go.kr/board/board.es?mid=a30402000000&bid=0030&act=view&list_no=366323&tag=&nPage=1|title=161 additional cases have been confirmed|author=<!--Not stated-->|date=24 February 2020|website=[[Korea Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]]|access-date=24 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 24 February 15 countries imposed travel restrictions to and from South Korea.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://edition.cnn.com/asia/live-news/coronavirus-outbreak-02-24-20-hnk-intl/h_303decf2bc32dd08ce587a7e9f3efafd|title=15 countries have travel restrictions on South Korea|date=24 February 2020|publisher=CNN|url-status=live|access-date=24 February 2020}}</ref> It was also reported that a senior health official overseeing the COVID-19 efforts in Daegu tested positive and was also a member of Shincheonji.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.scmp.com/week-asia/health-environment/article/3052129/coronavirus-infected-health-official-leading-south|title=Coronavirus: infected health official leading South Korea's fight against Covid-19 is member of Shincheonji Church of Jesus doomsday cult|last=Park|first=Chan-kyong|date=24 February 2020|website=[[South China Morning Post]]|access-date=25 February 2020|quote=Official in charge of fight against the virus in western Daegu admits being member of cult after testing positive; 50 coworkers quarantined}}</ref><ref name=\":750tested\">{{cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/world-nation/story/2020-02-27/south-korea-coronavirus-cases-surveillance|title=Were you on this bus with a coronavirus patient? South Korea is on the hunt for infections|last=Kim|first=Victoria|date=27 February 2020|website=[[Los Angeles Times]]|access-date=28 February 2020|quote=Even a public health official in charge of infection prevention in Seo-gu in Daegu was revealed to be a member of the church after he was diagnosed with the virus. Many members hide their affiliation with the controversial church. More than 750,000 signed a petition to the South Korean president urging that the church be disbanded. Authorities in Gyeonggi province raided the group\u2019s headquarters in the city of Gwacheon, alleging that the church had been slow to turn over its list of members. South Korean officials said they would track down and test all 245,000 members of the church.}}</ref> Within a few days, a petition to the nation's president urging for the disbandment of the church had over 750,000 signatures. Their headquarters in [[Gwacheon]] was raided by law enforcement; government officials said all 245,000 members of the religious group would be found and tested.<ref name=\":750tested\" /> On 28 February, over 2,000 confirmed cases were reported,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cdc.go.kr/board/board.es?mid=a30402000000&bid=0030|title=The Updates of COVID-19 in Republic of Korea As of 28 February, 2020|author=<!--Not stated-->|website=[[Korea Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]]|access-date=28 February 2020}}</ref> rising to 3,150 on 29 February.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://seekingalpha.com/news/3547240-south-korea-reports-record-jump-in-coronavirus-cases|title=South Korea reports a record jump in coronavirus cases|last=Hoffmann|first=SA Eli|date=29 February 2020|website=Seeking Alpha|access-date=1 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==== Criticism of South Korean response ====\nThe [[Ministry of Health and Welfare (South Korea)|Ministry of Health and Welfare]] has been criticized for unilaterally implementing [[Telehealth|telephone consultation]] and prescription without discussing with the [[Korea Medical Association]], and for not restricting traffic from China despite several warnings from the association and a petition proposed by the society.<ref name=\"AutoDW-232\"/><ref name=\"AutoDW-233\"/>\n\nOn 22 February, the South Korean government apologized for calling the virus \"[[Daegu]] Corona 19\" in an official report. The term has been widespread on social media and raises concerns about discrimination.<ref name=\"AutoDW-234\"/>\n\nMore than 1.5 million South Koreans have signed a [[petition]] to [[Impeachment|impeach]] President [[Moon Jae-in]] over what they claim is the government's mishandling of the outbreak.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Kim |first1=Suki |title=How South Korea Lost Control of Its Coronavirus Outbreak |url=https://www.newyorker.com/news/news-desk/how-south-korea-lost-control-of-its-coronavirus-outbreak |work=The New Yorker |date=4 March 2020}}</ref> On 6 March, the South Korean government has only entry restricted to Japanese citizens out of 102 countries that blocked Korea. The action has been widespread on social media and raises concerns about [[Anti-Japanese sentiment in Korea|anti-Japanese discrimination]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.chosun.com/site/data/html_dir/2020/03/06/2020030603059.html|title=[\uc0ac\uc124] \u65e5 \ub4a4\ub2a6\uac8c\ub77c\ub3c4 \u4e2d \ucc28\ub2e8, \uc138\uacc4\uace0\ub9bd \uc6b0\ub9ac\ub294 \u65e5\uc5d0\ub9cc \ubd84\ub178|date=7 March 2020|website=news.chosun.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://headlines.yahoo.co.jp/hl?a=20200307-00010006-fnnprimev-kr|title=\u65e5\u672c\u306e\u5165\u56fd\u5236\u9650\u306b\u97d3\u56fd\u6fc0\u6012\u3001\u77db\u76fe\u3060\u3089\u3051\u306e\"\u53cd\u65e5\"\u5bfe\u6297\u7b56\uff08FNN.jp\u30d7\u30e9\u30a4\u30e0\u30aa\u30f3\u30e9\u30a4\u30f3\uff09|website=Yahoo!\u30cb\u30e5\u30fc\u30b9}}</ref>\n\n=== Turkey ===\n{{main|2020 coronavirus pandemic in Turkey}}\nOn 10 January 2020, the Ministry of Health set up the [[Coronavirus Scientific Advisory Board (Turkey)|Coronavirus Scientific Advisory Board]].<ref name=\"h1\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.hurriyet.com.tr/gundem/bilim-kurulu-nedir-saglik-bakanligi-bilim-kurulu-uyeleri-kimlerdir-41478813 |title=Bilim Kurulu nedir? Sa\u011fl\u0131k Bakanl\u0131\u011f\u0131 Bilim Kurulu \u00fcyeleri kimlerdir? |date=26 March 2020 |work=[[H\u00fcrriyet]] |access-date=28 March 2020 |language=tr}}</ref> It consists of 26 members specialized in fields such as chest diseases, [[infectious diseases]] and [[clinical microbiology]].<ref name=\"a1\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.aksam.com.tr/guncel/son-dakikia-bilim-kurulu-toplantisi-ne-zaman-koronavirus-bilim-kurulu-ne-zaman-kuruldu-uye/haber-1056513 |title=Koranavir\u00fcs Bilim Kurulu ne zaman kuruldu, \u00fcyeleri kimlerdir? \u0130\u015fte Bilim Kurulu ile ilgili merak edilenler... |date=26 March 2020 |work=[[Ak\u015fam]] |access-date=26 March 2020 |language=tr}}</ref> The number of board members later increased to 31 with the joining of experts and academics in [[virology]], [[internal medicine]] and [[intensive care medicine]].<ref name=\"h1\" />\n\nIn the early hours of 11 March 2020 ([[UTC+03:00]]), the [[Ministry of Health (Turkey)|Minister of Health]] [[Fahrettin Koca]] announced that a Turkish man who had contracted the virus while travelling in Europe was the country's first confirmed coronavirus case.<ref name=\"daily.sabah.1\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.dailysabah.com/turkey/turkey-confirms-first-coronavirus-case-a-man-back-from-europe/news |title=Turkey confirms first coronavirus patient, recently returned from Europe |date=11 March 2020 |publisher=Daily Sabah |access-date=11 March 2020}}</ref> The patient had been placed in isolation at an undisclosed hospital, and family members of the patient were put under observation.<ref name=\"daily.sabah.1\" />\n\nOn 12 March 2020, after a meeting between President [[Recep Tayyip Erdo\u011fan]] and the rest of the Turkish government, Press Secretary [[\u0130brahim Kal\u0131n]] announced that primary schools, middle schools, and high schools in Turkey would be closed starting from 16 March 2020 for a week. Universities would also be closed for three weeks. Sports matches would be played [[Behind closed doors (sport)|behind closed doors]] in the stadiums until the end of April. The president also postponed all his overseas visits.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.hurriyet.com.tr/gundem/son-dakika-haberleri-bestepede-corona-virus-toplantisi-basladi-41467463 |title=Son dakika haberleri: Be\u015ftepe'deki corona vir\u00fcs toplant\u0131s\u0131 sona erdi! Okullar tatil edildi |url-status=live |access-date=12 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.aa.com.tr/tr/koronavirus/cumhurbaskanligi-sozcusu-kalin-ilk-orta-ve-liseler-1-hafta-universiteler-3-hafta-tatil-edilecek/1763918 |title=Cumhurba\u015fkanl\u0131\u011f\u0131 S\u00f6zc\u00fcs\u00fc Kal\u0131n: \u0130lk, orta ve liseler 1 hafta \u00fcniversiteler 3 hafta tatil edilecek |url-status=live |access-date=12 March 2020}}</ref> At the press conference held on 25 March, the [[Ministry of National Education (Turkey)|Minister of National Education]] [[Ziya Sel\u00e7uk]] announced that remote teaching would continue until 30 April.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.haberler.com/son-dakika-okullara-verilen-ara-uzatildi-13053581-haberi/ |title=Son Dakika: Okullara verilen ara uzat\u0131ld\u0131 |date=25 March 2020 |website=haberler.com |access-date=25 March 2020}}</ref> On 26 March, President of the [[Council of Higher Education (Turkey)|Council of Higher Education]] Yekta Sara\u00e7 stated that there would be no in-person teaching at universities in the remainder of the spring semester, and that they would continue with remote education only.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://tr.sputniknews.com/turkiye/202003261041691008-yok-baskani-universitelerde-bahar-doneminde-yuz-yuze-egitim-yapilmayacak-yks-ertelendi/ |title=Y\u00d6K Ba\u015fkan\u0131: \u00dcniversitelerde bahar d\u00f6neminde y\u00fcz y\u00fcze e\u011fitim yap\u0131lmayacak, YKS 25\u201326 Temmuz'a ertelendi |date=26 March 2020 |publisher=Sputnik Turkey |access-date=26 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 21 March, the [[Ministry of Transport and Infrastructure (Turkey)|Ministry of Transport and Infrastructure]] a total [[curfew]] for those who are over the age 65 or chronically ill.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.hurriyet.com.tr/gundem/son-dakika-haberi-icisleri-bakanligi-duyurdu-65-yas-ustune-disari-cikma-sinirlandirildi-41474569 |title=Son dakika haberler: \u0130\u00e7i\u015fleri Bakanl\u0131\u011f\u0131 duyurdu! 65 ya\u015f \u00fcst\u00fcne soka\u011fa \u00e7\u0131kma yasa\u011f\u0131 |date=21 March 2020 |website=[[H\u00fcrriyet]] |language=Turkish |access-date=21 March 2020}}</ref> On 27 March, the [[Ministry of the Interior (Turkey)|Ministry of the Interior]] issued a new statement regarding gatherings during weekends, announcing that starting from 28\u201329 March, having picnics, fishing at the shores, doing physical exercise outside (including running and walking on the weekends in city and town centers) would be banned until the virus spread has been contained. It was also stated that, should they deem it necessary, local authorities may extend these new measures to weekdays.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.icisleri.gov.tr/koronavirus-salgini-ile-mucadele-kapsaminda-park-mesire-piknik-yerleri-ile-ilgili-ek-genelge |title=Koronavir\u00fcs Salg\u0131n\u0131 ile M\u00fccadele Kapsam\u0131nda Park, Mesire, Piknik Yerleri \u0130le \u0130lgili Ek Genelge |date=26 March 2020 |publisher=T.C. \u0130\u00e7i\u015fleri Bakanl\u0131\u011f\u0131 |access-date=26 March 2020}}</ref> Also on 27 March, President Erdo\u011fan announced that all overseas flights were terminated, adding that intercity travel was subject to permission by the state governors, and that places such as picnic areas, forests and historical sites would be closed on the weekend.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.hurriyet.com.tr/gundem/son-dakika-haberi-cumhurbaskani-erdogan-aciklama-yapacak-41479930 |title=Son dakika haberi: Cumhurba\u015fkan\u0131 Erdo\u011fan yeni corona vir\u00fcs \u00f6nlemlerini tek tek a\u00e7\u0131klad\u0131! |date=28 March 2020 |work=[[H\u00fcrriyet]] |access-date=28 March 2020 |trans-title=Breaking news: President Erdo\u011fan announced new corona virus measures one by one!}}</ref> On 3 April 2020, President Erdo\u011fan announced a 15-day entry ban to 30 [[Metropolitan municipalities in Turkey|metropolitan municipalities]] as well as [[Zonguldak]]. Also, the curfew was extended to people younger than 20 years old. Using masks in public places became mandatory.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.cnnturk.com/turkiye/son-dakika-cumhurbaskani-erdogandan-onemli-aciklamalar030420 |title=Son dakika... Cumhurba\u015fkan\u0131 Erdo\u011fan yeni tedbirleri a\u00e7\u0131klad\u0131! 20 ya\u015f alt\u0131na soka\u011fa \u00e7\u0131kma yasa\u011f\u0131 |date=3 April 2020 |work=CNN T\u00fcrk |access-date=3 April 2020 |language=tr}}</ref>\n\n==== Criticism of Turkish response ====\nThe announced {{Turkish lira}}100 billion economic measures package, set to be provided by the government, was criticized by institutions and individuals, including economists and politicians. The lack of a detailed action plan was the center of criticism. Additionally, at a time when people were encouraged to stay at home, the government was criticized for allowing airline passenger transport and tax reductions that support tourism. Critics asked for lowering the down payment of housing loans and emphasized on the need to provide employment support to different sectors.<ref name=\"BBC-economics\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/turkce/haberler-dunya-51958762 |title=Koronavir\u00fcs ekonomik tedbir paketi: Kime, hangi g\u00fcvence sunuluyor? |date=19 March 2020 |publisher=BBC Turkish |access-date=25 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://tr.euronews.com/2020/03/19/ekonomide-covid-19-turkiye-nin-100-milyar-tl-onlem-paketi-ekonomistler-ne-diyor-corona |title=Ekonomide Covid-19: T\u00fcrkiye'nin 100 milyar TL \u00f6nlem paketi i\u00e7in ekonomistler ne diyor? |last=Tokyay |first=Menekse |date=19 March 2020 |publisher=Euronews Turkish |access-date=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe donation campaign initiated by President [[Recep Tayyip Erdo\u011fan]] was supported by representatives of the ruling party, members of the oppositions had a less favorable reaction to it.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.diken.com.tr/milli-dayanisma-kampanyasina-destek-de-var-elestiri-de/ |title='Milli Dayan\u0131\u015fma Kampanyas\u0131'na destek de var ele\u015ftiri de |date=30 March 2020 |website=diken.com.tr |access-date=31 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.independentturkish.com/node/155576/erdo%C4%9Fan%E2%80%99%C4%B1n-a%C3%A7%C4%B1klad%C4%B1%C4%9F%C4%B1-ba%C4%9F%C4%B1%C5%9F-kampanyas%C4%B1na-tepki-g%C3%B6sterenler-eski-ak-partili-vekil-de |title=Erdo\u011fan'\u0131n a\u00e7\u0131klad\u0131\u011f\u0131 ba\u011f\u0131\u015f kampanyas\u0131na tepki g\u00f6sterenler: Eski AK Partili vekil de listede |date=30 March 2020 |publisher=Independent Turkish |access-date=31 March 2020}}</ref> After the government's decision to take money from the income of several institutions in order to make donations to this campaign, the [[Confederation of Public Employees' Unions]] filed a criminal complaint as a result of the salary cuts of the staff of many institutions such as MEB, BOTA\u015e, General Directorate of Forestry, [[Ministry of Justice (Turkey)|Ministry of Justice]], [[Constitutional Court of Turkey|Constitutional Court]] and Social Service Provincial Directorates.<ref>[https://www.gazeteduvar.com.tr/gundem/2020/04/02/kesk-zorunlu-bagisa-suc-duyurusu-yapacagiz/ KESK: Zorunlu ba\u011f\u0131\u015fa su\u00e7 duyurusu yapaca\u011f\u0131z]</ref> Additionally, a similar donation campaign initiated by the metropolitan municipalities with [[Republican People's Party (Turkey)|CHP]] administration was terminated by the [[Ministry of the Interior (Turkey)|Ministry of the Interior]] and their bank accounts were blocked. Regarding this decision, the Ankara Bar Association issued a statement, saying: \"Although the aforementioned circular and blocking process enforced by the Ministry of the Interior are clearly unlawful, the provision of social services belongs neither exclusively to the local governments nor to the central government.\"<ref>[https://www.gazeteduvar.com.tr/gundem/2020/04/02/ankara-barosu-icislerinin-bagis-genelgesi-hukuksuz/ Ankara Barosu: \u0130\u00e7i\u015flerinin ba\u011f\u0131\u015f genelgesi hukuksuz]</ref>\n\n====Other countries and territories====\n{{div col|colwidth=15em}}\n\n* [[Image:Flag of Afghanistan.svg|25px]] '''[[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Afghanistan#Prevention measures|Afghanistan]]'''\n* [[Image:Flag of Armenia.svg|25px]] '''[[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Armenia#Timeline|Armenia]]'''\n* [[Image:Flag of Azerbaijan.svg|25px]] '''[[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Azerbaijan#Timeline|Azerbaijan]]'''\n* [[Image:Flag of Bahrain.svg|25px]] '''[[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Bahrain#Timeline|Bahrain]]'''\n* [[Image:Flag of Bangladesh.svg|25px]] '''[[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Bangladesh#Government response|Bangladesh]]'''\n* [[Image:Flag of Bhutan.svg|25px]] '''[[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Bhutan#Timeline|Bhutan]]'''\n* [[Image:Flag of Brunei.svg|25px]] '''[[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Brunei#Timeline|Brunei]]'''\n* [[Image:Flag of Cambodia.svg|25px]] '''[[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Cambodia#Timeline|Cambodia]]'''\n* [[Image:Flag of East Timor.svg|25px]] '''[[2020 coronavirus pandemic in East Timor#Timeline|East Timor]]'''\n* [[Image:Flag of Georgia.svg|25px]] '''[[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Georgia (country)#Timeline|Goergia]]'''\n* [[Image:Flag of Hong Kong.svg|25px]] '''[[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Hong Kong#Timeline|Hong Kong]]'''\n* [[Image:Flag of Iraq.svg|25px]] '''[[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Iraq#Government response and impacts|Iraq]]'''\n* [[Image:Flag of Israel.svg|25px]] '''[[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Israel#Government response|Israel]]'''\n* [[Image:Flag of Jordan.svg|25px]] '''[[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Jordan#Government response|Jordan]]'''\n* [[Image:Flag of Kazakhstan.svg|25px]] '''[[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Kazakhstan#Government responses|Kazakhstan]]'''\n* [[Image:Flag of Kuwait.svg|25px]] '''[[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Kuwait#Response|Kuwait]]'''\n* [[Image:Flag of Kyrgyzstan.svg|25px]] '''[[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Kyrgyzstan#Timeline|Kyrgyzstan]]'''\n* [[Image:Flag of Laos.svg|25px]] '''[[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Laos#Timeline|Laos]]'''\n* [[Image:Flag of Lebanon.svg|25px]] '''[[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Lebanon#Containment|Lebanon]]'''\n* [[Image:Flag of Macau.svg|25px]] '''[[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Macau#Response and impact|Macau]]'''\n* [[Image:Flag of Malaysia.svg|25px]] '''[[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Malaysia#Preventive measures by government|Malaysia]]'''\n* [[Image:Flag of Maldives.svg|25px]] '''[[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the Maldives#Timeline|Maldives]]'''\n* [[Image:Flag of Mongolia.svg|25px]] '''[[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Mongolia#Timeline|Mongolia]]'''\n* [[Image:Flag of Myanmar.svg|25px]] '''[[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Myanmar#Timeline|Myanmar]]'''\n* [[Image:Flag of Nepal.svg|15px]] '''[[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Nepal#Timeline|Nepal]]'''\n* [[Image:Flag of Oman.svg|25px]] '''[[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Oman#Prevention measures|Oman]]'''\n* [[Image:Flag of Pakistan.svg|25px]] '''[[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Pakistan#Prevention measures and response|Pakistan]]'''\n* [[Image:Flag of Palestine.svg|25px]] '''[[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Palestine#Timeline|Palestine]]'''\n* [[Image:Flag of Qatar.svg|25px]] '''[[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Qatar#Timeline|Qatar]]'''\n* [[Image:Flag of Russia.svg|25px]] '''[[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Russia#Government responses|Russia]]'''\n* [[Image:Flag of Saudi Arabia.svg|25px]] '''[[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Saudi Arabia#Government responses|Saudi Arabia]]'''\n* [[Image:Flag of Singapore.svg|25px]] '''[[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Singapore#Preventive measures|Singapore]]'''\n* [[Image:Flag of Sri Lanka.svg|25px]] '''[[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Sri Lanka#Response|Sri Lanka]]'''\n* [[Image:Flag of Syria.svg|25px]] '''[[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Syria#Timeline|Syria]]'''\n* [[Image:Flag of Taiwan.svg|25px]] '''[[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Taiwan#Preventive measures|Taiwan]]'''\n* [[Image:Flag of Thailand.svg|25px]] '''[[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Thailand#Preventive measures|Thailand]]'''\n* [[Image:Flag of United Arab Emirates.svg|25px]] '''[[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United Arab Emirates#Government responses|United Arab Emirates]]'''\n* [[Image:Flag of Uzbekistan.svg|25px]] '''[[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Uzbekistan#Timeline|Uzbekistan]]'''\n* [[Image:Flag of Vietnam.svg|25px]] '''[[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Vietnam#Government responses|Vietnam]]'''\n* [[Image:Flag of Yemen.svg|25px]] '''[[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Yemen|Yemen]]'''\n\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Europe==\n\n=== Italy ===\n{{Main|2020 coronavirus pandemic in Italy}}\n[[File:Emergenza coronavirus (49496308758).jpg|thumb|right|[[Protezione Civile|Civil Protection]] volunteers carrying out health checks at the [[Guglielmo Marconi Airport]] in [[Bologna]]]]\n\nThe outbreak was confirmed to have spread to Italy on 31 January 2020, when two Chinese tourists tested positive for SARS-CoV-2 in Rome.<ref name=\"Corriere_20Jan\">{{cite web|url=https://www.corriere.it/cronache/20_gennaio_30/coronavirus-italia-corona-9d6dc436-4343-11ea-bdc8-faf1f56f19b7.shtml|title=Coronavirus: Primi due casi in Italia|date=31 January 2020|trans-title=Coronavirus: First two cases in Italy|website=Corriere della sera|language=it|accessdate=31 January 2020}}</ref> In response, the Italian government suspended all flights to and from China and declared a state of emergency, with Prime Minister [[Giuseppe Conte]] stating that Italy is the first EU country to take this precautionary measure.<ref name=\"thelocal-flight\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.thelocal.it/20200131/italy-suspends-all-china-flights-after-coronavirus-cases-confirmed-in-rome/|title=Italy suspends all China flights as coronavirus cases confirmed in Rome|date=31 January 2020|website=THELOCAL|access-date=26 February 2020}}</ref> On 31 January, the [[Council of Ministers of Italy|Italian Council of Ministers]] appointed [[Angelo Borrelli]], head of the [[Protezione Civile|Civil Protection]], as Special Commissioner for the COVID-19 Emergency.<ref>{{Cite web|url= https://tg24.sky.it/politica/approfondimenti/angelo-borrelli-chi-e.html |title=Chi \u00e8 Angelo Borrelli, nominato Commissario per l'emergenza coronavirus |website=tg24.sky.it |language=it |accessdate=7 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fanpage.it/politica/coronavirus-angelo-borrelli-nominato-commissario-straordinario-ecco-chi-e/|title=Coronavirus, Angelo Borrelli commissario straordinario: potr\u00e0 anche requisire gli hotel|website=Fanpage}}</ref> A unassociated cluster of [[COVID-19]] cases was later further detected starting with 16 confirmed cases in [[Lombardy]] on 21 February,<ref name=\"ThomReut_IT_16cluster_21Feb\">{{cite news|last1=Anzolin|first1=Elisa|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-health-italy/coronavirus-outbreak-grows-in-northern-italy-16-cases-reported-in-one-day-idUSKBN20F0UI|title=coronavirus pandemic grows in northern Italy, 16 cases reported in one day|date=21 February 2020|accessdate=21 February 2020|url-status=live <!-- live|dead|unfit|usurped -->|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200221225322/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-health-italy/coronavirus-outbreak-grows-in-northern-italy-16-cases-reported-in-one-day-idUSKBN20F0UI|archivedate=21 February 2020|agency=[[Thomson Reuters]]|last2=Amante|first2=Angelo|url-access=<!-- (subscription/registration/limited) default=free -->}}</ref> an additional 60 cases on 22 February, and Italy's first deaths reported on the same day.{{citation needed|date=March 2020}}\n\nThe Ministry of Health announced new guidelines for reporting cases on 27 February in response to the previous blanket testing that caused case numbers to surge and inflamed public panic.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.repubblica.it/cronaca/2020/02/28/news/_polmoniti_anomale_a_meta_gennaio_cosi_e_nato_il_focolaio_di_codogno_-249759796/|title=Coronavirus, polmoniti anomale a met\u00e0 gennaio: \"Cos\u00ec \u00e8 nato il focolaio di Codogno\"|date=27 February 2020|website=la Repubblica|language=it|access-date=28 February 2020}}</ref> It would no longer report asymptomatic cases (swabs taken from patients which tested positive but were not showing symptoms) which counted as 40 to 50% of all reported cases at the time. These people would undergo isolation at home and would be followed up with new tests until they were negative.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.repubblica.it/cronaca/2020/02/28/news/cambia_il_metodo_di_conteggio_esclusi_i_positivi_asintomatici-249765660/|title=Cambia il metodo di conteggio: esclusi i positivi asintomatici|date=27 February 2020|website=la Repubblica|language=it|access-date=28 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://abcnews.go.com/Health/wireStory/italy-virus-count-methods-agencys-urging-69254949|title=Italy blasts virus panic as it eyes new testing criteria|publisher=ABC News|access-date=28 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 22 February, the [[Council of Ministers of Italy|Italian Council of Ministers]] announced a new decree law to contain the outbreak, including quarantining more than 50,000 people from 11 different municipalities in [[northern Italy]].<ref name=\"AutoDW-201\"/> Prime Minister [[Giuseppe Conte]] said \"In the outbreak areas, entry and exit will not be provided. Suspension of work activities and sport events has already been ordered in those areas.\"<ref name=\"AutoDW-202\"/><ref name=\"AutoDW-203\"/> Punishments for violating of the lockdown range from a fine of 206 euros to 3 months imprisonment.<ref name=\"AutoDW-204\"/> [[Italian army|Italian military]] and law enforcement agencies were instructed to secure and implement the lockdown.<ref name=\"AutoDW-205\"/>\n\nOn 3 March, Chinese authorities reported that on March first and second, eight virus victims who had returned to the county of Qingtian, in East China's Zhejiang province, were suffering from the virus. All eight appear to have acquired Covid-19 in the northern town of [[Bergamo, Italy]], a virus-ravaged municipality, where they had worked at a restaurant, Qingtian officials said. Chinese authorities called these \"backflow cases\" \u2014 virus carriers who contract the disease outside China, then bring it back to their homeland.<ref>Flynn Murphy, Zhang Erchi and Ye Zhanqi, [https://www.caixinglobal.com/2020-03-03/china-faces-growing-virus-threat-from-outside-the-country-101523601.html \"China Faces Growing Virus Threat From Outside the Country\"], ''Caixin'', 3 March 2020</ref>\n\nOn 4 March, the Italian government ordered the full closure of all schools and universities nationwide as Italy reached 100 deaths. Additionally, all major sporting events, including Serie A football matches, would be held behind closed doors until April.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Palermo|first=Angela Giuffrida Lorenzo Tondo in|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/04/italy-orders-closure-of-schools-and-universities-due-to-coronavirus|title=Italy orders closure of all schools and universities due to coronavirus|date=4 March 2020|work=The Guardian|access-date=4 March 2020|last2=Beaumont|first2=Peter|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> On 9 March, all sport was suspended completely for at least one month.<ref>{{Cite news | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/51808683 | title=Coronavirus: All sport in Italy suspended because of outbreak| work=BBC Sport| date=9 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n{{main|2020 Italy coronavirus lockdown}}\nOn 21 February, at least ten towns in the Lombardy and [[Veneto]] regions of Italy, with a total population of 50,000, were locked down in quarantine procedure following an outbreak in [[Codogno]] in Lombardy. Police mandated a curfew closing all public buildings and controlling access through police checkpoints to the so-called 'red zone' which is enforced by penalties for violations ranging from a \u20ac206 fine to three months of imprisonment against trespassers who are not health or supply workers.<ref name=\"AutoDW-204\"/> The government of Giuseppe Conte said that sending in the armed forces to enforce the lockdown was a possibility.<ref name=\"AutoDW-205\"/> The governor of [[Basilicata]], [[Vito Bardi]], instituted a mandatory 14-day quarantine for people arriving from areas in northern Italy affected by the outbreak on 24 February.<ref name=\"Repubblica_24Feb2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.repubblica.it/cronaca/2020/02/24/news/coronavirus_149_i_casi_confermati_conte_i_contagi_possono_crescere_-249427098/|title=Coronavirus, quarto morto, \u00e8 un 84enne di Bergamo. Sette regioni coinvolte per 30 milioni di italiani|date=24 February 2020|website=la Repubblica|language=it|access-date=24 February 2020}}</ref> On the same day, 500 extra police officers were assigned to patrol the quarantined areas in [[Lodi, Lombardy|Lodi]] and Veneto.<ref name=\"Repubblica_24Feb2\"/>\n\nOn the morning of 8 March 2020, Conte said that much of Italy's northern territories, including Milan and Venice, would be quarantined within their region.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Horowitz |first1=Jason |title=Italy Locks Down Much of the Country's North Over the Coronavirus |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/07/world/europe/coronavirus-italy.html|accessdate=8 March 2020 |work=The New York Times |date=7 March 2020}}</ref> Conte said the country was locking down all of the populous Lombardy region, with movement restrictions applying to about 16 million people.<ref name=Italia>[https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/europe/italy-coronavirus-milan-lombardy-lockdowns/2020/03/07/403fcea2-60b3-11ea-ac50-18701e14e06d_story.html To contain coronavirus, Italy will restrict movement across much of its northern region, including the city of Milan], ''[[Washington Post]]'', Chico Harlan and Stefano Pitrelli, 7 March 2020. Retrieved 8 March 2020.</ref> This will be the most aggressive response taken in any region beyond China, and will paralyse the wealthiest parts of the country as Italy attempts to constrain the rapid spread of the disease.<ref name=Italia/> On 8 March 2020, there have been 7,375 confirmed cases, and 366 deaths in Italy.<ref name=JHMap/>\n\nOn the evening of 9 March 2020, the quarantine was expanded to all of Italy.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-51810673|title=Coronavirus: Italy extends strict quarantine measures nationwide|access-date=2020-03-09}}</ref>\n\n==== Criticism of Italian response ====\nItaly's government has drawn criticism from scientists and WHO, for its decision to suspend direct flights to mainland China that while sounding \"tough\" on paper, was ineffective as \"people can still arrive from risk areas via indirect routes.\"<ref name=\":21\"/> Walter Ricciardi, professor of Hygiene and Public Health at the [[Universit\u00e0 Cattolica del Sacro Cuore]] in Rome and a member of the European Advisory Committee on Health Research has said \"Italy was wrong, closing flights from China is of no use when there are indirect ones.\"<ref name=\"AutoDW-237\"/>\n\nItaly's government has also been criticised for not testing or enforcing lockdowns sufficiently in some regions,<ref name=\"Harvard\">{{Citation|title=Lessons from Italy's Response to Coronavirus|url=http://hbr.org/2020/03/lessons-from-italys-response-to-coronavirus|language=en|website=Harvard Business Review|date=27 March 2020}}</ref> sending mixed messages,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ecfr.eu/article/commentary_uncharted_territory_italys_response_to_the_coronavirus|title=Uncharted territory: Italy's response to the coronavirus|website=ECFR|language=en|access-date=5 April 2020}}</ref> and downplaying the severity of the situation.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Horowitz|first=Jason|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/21/world/europe/italy-coronavirus-center-lessons.html|title=Italy, Pandemic's New Epicenter, Has Lessons for the World|date=21 March 2020|work=The New York Times|access-date=5 April 2020|last2=Bubola|first2=Emma|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|last3=Povoledo|first3=Elisabetta}}</ref> Criticism followed disclosures by Italian Prime Minister [[Giuseppe Conte]] that protocols had not been followed at the hospital in Codogno, Lombardy that treated \"patient 1\" which \"certainly contributed to the spread\" of the virus in Italy, with Conte responding to inquiries by journalists on what protocol was broken with \"This is not the time for controversy.\"<ref name=\"AutoDW-238\"/> In response to a statement by Conte that the central government may need to \"revoke regional health policy powers,\" [[President of Lombardy]] [[Attilio Fontana]] called Conte's statement \"fascist\" and \"talking nonsense.\"<ref name=\":21\" />\n\nOn 8 March, plans by the government to quarantine 16 million people in Northern Italy were leaked early by a national newspaper, causing thousands of people to flee the region before it took place. Conte condemned the leak, calling it \"unacceptable\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/12-mistakes-made-that-helped-spread-coronavirus-around-the-world-2020-2#in-northern-italy-plans-by-the-government-to-quarantine-16-million-people-on-march-8-were-leaked-early-by-a-national-newspaper-causing-thousands-of-people-to-flee-the-region-before-the-measures-took-place-3|title=21 mistakes by public health officials and ordinary people that helped spread the coronavirus around the world|last=Ankel|first=Sophia|date=|website=Business Insider|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=5 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== France ===\n{{Main|2020 coronavirus pandemic in France}}\n{{Expand section|date=April 2020}}\nOn 24 January 2020, the first case of COVID-19 in France was confirmed in [[Bordeaux]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Jacob |first1=Etienne |title=Coronavirus: trois premiers cas confirm\u00e9s en France, deux d'entre eux vont bien |url=https://www.lefigaro.fr/sciences/coronavirus-trois-premiers-cas-confirmes-en-france-20200124 |website=Le Figaro.fr |accessdate=7 March 2020 |language=fr |date=24 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 16 March 2020, [[President Macron]] announced a nationwide lockdown for 15 days starting on 17 March midday, through a decree prohibiting all but essential outings.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/europe/coronavirus-france-lockdown-cases-update-covid-19-macron-a9405136.html|title=France imposes 15-day lockdown as part of emergency coronavirus response|date=16 March 2020|website=The Independent}}</ref>\n\n=== Germany ===\n{{Main|2020 coronavirus pandemic in Germany}}\n{{Expand section|date=April 2020}}\nAt the end of January 2020, the first cases occurred in Bavaria in direct connection with the outbreak in Wuhan, China. After initial stagnation, several other cases were reported in different locations. During carnival in February, Heinsberg in Northrhine Westfalia was most affected, and case numbers steadily increased. By the second week of March, all federal states were affected and the first fatality was reported.<ref name=\"aa\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.auswaertiges-amt.de/blob/2294930/33e99dc559cfe3dbda8e7ae65b39c3be/ncov-data.pdf |title=COVID 19 |date=2020-03-27 |work=Gesundheitsdienst, Ausw\u00e4rtiges Amt |access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>\nAs of 28 March 2020 the incidence was highest in the city state of Hamburg, followed by Baden-W\u00fcrttemberg and Bavaria.<ref name=\"rki\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.rki.de/DE/Content/InfAZ/N/Neuartiges_Coronavirus/Situationsberichte/2020-03-28-en.pdfFile |title= Coronavirus Disease 2019  |date=2020-03-27 |work=Daily Situation Report of the Robert Koch Institute}}</ref>\nThe [[Robert Koch Institute]] recommended an initial strategy of containment, until more cases would occur than could be traced back to an known case. The next phase of the epidemic, namely community transmission, was assumed to have begun first in Heinsberg, where a strategy of protection of vulnerable groups was adopted.<ref name=\"aa\"/>\n\n=== Greece ===\n{{Main|2020 coronavirus pandemic in Greece}}\nOn 26 February, the first case in Greece was confirmed, a 38-year-old woman from [[Thessaloniki]] who had recently visited [[Northern Italy]].<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-health-greece-idUSKCN20K1IA|title=Greece confirms first coronavirus case|date=26 February 2020|work=Reuters|access-date=29 March 2020|url-status=live|language=en}}</ref> Within the next days, health and state authorities issued precautionary guidelines and recommendations, while measures up to that point were taken locally and included the closure of schools and the suspension of cultural events in the affected areas (particularly [[Elis (regional unit)|Ilia]], [[Achaea]] and [[Zakynthos]]).<ref name=\":02\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.newsit.gr/ellada/koronoios-14-akoma-krousmata-stin-ellad/2988717/|title=\u039a\u03bf\u03c1\u03bf\u03bd\u03bf\u03ca\u03cc\u03c2: 14 \u03b1\u03ba\u03cc\u03bc\u03b1 \u03ba\u03c1\u03bf\u03cd\u03c3\u03bc\u03b1\u03c4\u03b1 \u03c3\u03c4\u03b7\u03bd \u0395\u03bb\u03bb\u03ac\u03b4\u03b1!|last=|first=|date=|website=www.newsit.gr|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref> Various municipalities around the country began disinfecting schools.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ieidiseis.gr/ellada/item/36906-koronoios-stin-ellada-proliptikes-apolymanseis-se-dimosia-ktiria-apo-ton-dimo-iliou|title=\u039a\u03bf\u03c1\u03bf\u03bd\u03bf\u03ca\u03cc\u03c2 \u03c3\u03c4\u03b7\u03bd \u0395\u03bb\u03bb\u03ac\u03b4\u03b1: \u03a0\u03c1\u03bf\u03bb\u03b7\u03c0\u03c4\u03b9\u03ba\u03ad\u03c2 \u03b1\u03c0\u03bf\u03bb\u03c5\u03bc\u03ac\u03bd\u03c3\u03b5\u03b9\u03c2 \u03c3\u03b5 \u03b4\u03b7\u03bc\u03cc\u03c3\u03b9\u03b1 \u03ba\u03c4\u03ae\u03c1\u03b9\u03b1 \u03b1\u03c0\u03cc \u03c4\u03bf\u03bd \u0394\u03ae\u03bc\u03bf \u0399\u03bb\u03af\u03bf\u03c5|last=iEidiseis|website=www.ieidiseis.gr|language=el-gr|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref> The Greek [[National Public Health Organization (Greece)|National Public Health Organization]] (NPHO), in collaboration with local authorities and doctors, is tracking and testing everyone who came in close contact with the confirmed carriers.<ref>{{cite Web|url=https://www.onmed.gr/ygeia-eidhseis/story/382322/koronoios-stin-patra-to-enato-kroysma|title=\u039a\u03bf\u03c1\u03bf\u03bd\u03b1\u03ca\u03cc\u03c2: \u0388\u03bd\u03b1\u03c4\u03bf \u03b5\u03c0\u03b9\u03b2\u03b5\u03b2\u03b1\u03b9\u03c9\u03bc\u03ad\u03bd\u03bf \u03ba\u03c1\u03bf\u03cd\u03c3\u03bc\u03b1 \u03c3\u03c4\u03b7\u03bd \u03a0\u03ac\u03c4\u03c1\u03b1|website=www.onmed.gr|language=el}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ant1news.gr/ygeia-periballon/article/561722/koronoios-deka-ta-kroysmata-stin-ellada|title=\u039a\u03bf\u03c1\u03bf\u03bd\u03bf\u03ca\u03cc\u03c2: \u0394\u03ad\u03ba\u03b1 \u03c4\u03b1 \u03ba\u03c1\u03bf\u03cd\u03c3\u03bc\u03b1\u03c4\u03b1 \u03c3\u03c4\u03b7\u03bd \u0395\u03bb\u03bb\u03ac\u03b4\u03b1|last=|first=|date=|website=antenna.gr|language=el|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>\n\nBy 10 March, with 89 confirmed cases and no deaths in the country,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.gr/news/ellada/story/210621/koronoios-stin-ellada-anakoinothikan-pente-nea-kroysmata|title=\u039a\u03bf\u03c1\u03c9\u03bd\u03bf\u03ca\u03cc\u03c2 \u03c3\u03c4\u03b7\u03bd \u0395\u03bb\u03bb\u03ac\u03b4\u03b1: \u0391\u03bd\u03b1\u03ba\u03bf\u03b9\u03bd\u03ce\u03b8\u03b7\u03ba\u03b1\u03bd \u03c0\u03ad\u03bd\u03c4\u03b5 \u03bd\u03ad\u03b1 \u03ba\u03c1\u03bf\u03cd\u03c3\u03bc\u03b1\u03c4\u03b1|last=|first=|date=10 March 2020|website=cnn.gr|language=el|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=29 March 2020}}</ref> the government decided to suspend the operation of all schools, universities, daycare centers and all other educational establishments nationwide and then, on 13 March, to close down all cafes, bars, museums, shopping centres, sports facilities and restaurants in the country.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.minedu.gov.gr/news/44308-10-03-20-prosorini-apagorefsi-tis-ekpaideftikis-leitourgias-olon-ton-ekpaideftikon-domon|title=\u03a5\u03a0\u039f\u03a5\u03a1\u0393\u0395\u0399\u039f \u03a0\u0391\u0399\u0394\u0395\u0399\u0391\u03a3 & \u0398\u03a1\u0397\u03a3\u039a\u0395\u03a5\u039c\u0391\u03a4\u03a9\u039d \u2013 10-03-20 \u03a0\u03c1\u03bf\u03c3\u03c9\u03c1\u03b9\u03bd\u03ae \u03b1\u03c0\u03b1\u03b3\u03cc\u03c1\u03b5\u03c5\u03c3\u03b7 \u03c4\u03b7\u03c2 \u03b5\u03ba\u03c0\u03b1\u03b9\u03b4\u03b5\u03c5\u03c4\u03b9\u03ba\u03ae\u03c2 \u03bb\u03b5\u03b9\u03c4\u03bf\u03c5\u03c1\u03b3\u03af\u03b1\u03c2 \u03cc\u03bb\u03c9\u03bd \u03c4\u03c9\u03bd \u03b5\u03ba\u03c0\u03b1\u03b9\u03b4\u03b5\u03c5\u03c4\u03b9\u03ba\u03ce\u03bd \u03b4\u03bf\u03bc\u03ce\u03bd|last=|first=|date=|website=www.minedu.gov.gr|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.capital.gr/epikairotita/3437285/sta-190-sunolika-ta-krousmata-stin-ellada-kleinoun-emporika-kentra-kafe-mpar|title=\u03a3\u03c4\u03b1 190 \u03c3\u03c5\u03bd\u03bf\u03bb\u03b9\u03ba\u03ac \u03c4\u03b1 \u03ba\u03c1\u03bf\u03cd\u03c3\u03bc\u03b1\u03c4\u03b1 \u03c3\u03c4\u03b7\u03bd \u0395\u03bb\u03bb\u03ac\u03b4\u03b1 \u2013 \u039a\u03bb\u03b5\u03af\u03bd\u03bf\u03c5\u03bd \u03b5\u03bc\u03c0\u03bf\u03c1\u03b9\u03ba\u03ac \u03ba\u03ad\u03bd\u03c4\u03c1\u03b1, \u03ba\u03b1\u03c6\u03ad, \u03bc\u03c0\u03b1\u03c1|last=Capital.gr|website=Capital.gr|language=el|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref> On 16 March, all retail shops were also closed and all services in all areas of religious worship of any religion or dogma were suspended. Supermarkets, pharmacies, food outlets that offer take-away and delivery only, as well as some other businesses, remained open.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.news247.gr/koinonia/koronoios-kleinoyn-ta-emporika-katastimata-se-karantina-osoi-erchontai-apo-exoteriko.7603146.html|title=\u039a\u03bf\u03c1\u03bf\u03bd\u03bf\u03ca\u03cc\u03c2: \u039a\u03bb\u03b5\u03af\u03bd\u03bf\u03c5\u03bd \u03c4\u03b1 \u03b5\u03bc\u03c0\u03bf\u03c1\u03b9\u03ba\u03ac \u03ba\u03b1\u03c4\u03b1\u03c3\u03c4\u03ae\u03bc\u03b1\u03c4\u03b1 \u2013 \u03a3\u03b5 \u03ba\u03b1\u03c1\u03b1\u03bd\u03c4\u03af\u03bd\u03b1 \u03cc\u03c3\u03bf\u03b9 \u03ad\u03c1\u03c7\u03bf\u03bd\u03c4\u03b1\u03b9 \u03b1\u03c0\u03cc \u03b5\u03be\u03c9\u03c4\u03b5\u03c1\u03b9\u03ba\u03cc|last=|first=|date=|website=www.news247.gr|language=el|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kathimerini.gr/1069449/article/epikairothta/politikh/anastellontai-oles-oi-8rhskeytikes-leitoyrgies-me-apofash-ths-kyvernhshs|title=\u0391\u03bd\u03b1\u03c3\u03c4\u03ad\u03bb\u03bb\u03bf\u03bd\u03c4\u03b1\u03b9 \u03cc\u03bb\u03b5\u03c2 \u03bf\u03b9 \u03b8\u03c1\u03b7\u03c3\u03ba\u03b5\u03c5\u03c4\u03b9\u03ba\u03ad\u03c2 \u03bb\u03b5\u03b9\u03c4\u03bf\u03c5\u03c1\u03b3\u03af\u03b5\u03c2 \u03bc\u03b5 \u03b1\u03c0\u03cc\u03c6\u03b1\u03c3\u03b7 \u03c4\u03b7\u03c2 \u03ba\u03c5\u03b2\u03ad\u03c1\u03bd\u03b7\u03c3\u03b7\u03c2 {{!}} Kathimerini|last=|first=|date=|website=www.kathimerini.gr|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref> On 18 and 19 March, the government announced a series of economic measures of more than 10 billion euros to support the economy, businesses and employees.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ethnos.gr/oikonomia/94785_koronoios-ta-metra-gia-ergazomenoys-ki-epiheiriseis|title=\u039a\u03bf\u03c1\u03bf\u03bd\u03bf\u03ca\u03cc\u03c2: \u03a4\u03b1 \u03bc\u03ad\u03c4\u03c1\u03b1 \u03b3\u03b9\u03b1 \u03b5\u03c1\u03b3\u03b1\u03b6\u03cc\u03bc\u03b5\u03bd\u03bf\u03c5\u03c2 \u03ba\u03b9 \u03b5\u03c0\u03b9\u03c7\u03b5\u03b9\u03c1\u03ae\u03c3\u03b5\u03b9\u03c2|last=|first=|date=2020-03-18|website=\u0388\u03b8\u03bd\u03bf\u03c2|language=el|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>\n\nOn 22 March, the Greek authorities announced significant restrictions on all nonessential transport and movement across the country, starting from 6 a.m. on 23 March. Movement outside the house is permitted only for specific reasons that include moving to or from the workplace, shopping for food or medicine, going to the bank, visiting a doctor or assisting a person in need of help and walking a pet or exercising outside individually or in pairs. Citizens leaving their home are required to carry their police ID or passport, as well as some type of attestation depending on the purpose of travel.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ekathimerini.com/250917/article/ekathimerini/news/full-lockdown-in-effect-from-monday-to-curb-coronavirus|title=Full lockdown in effect from Monday to curb coronavirus {{!}} Kathimerini|last=|first=|date=|website=www.ekathimerini.com|language=English|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref> All passenger flights to and from Italy, Spain, Albania, North Macedonia, Turkey, the United Kingdom, the Netherlands and Germany are suspended until 15 May,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ekathimerini.com/251736/article/ekathimerini/news/greece-extends-flight-ban-for-six-countries-until-may-15|title=Greece extends flight ban for six countries until May 15 {{!}} Kathimerini|website=www.ekathimerini.com|language=English|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Hellenic Civil Aviation Authority|first=|url=http://www.ypa.gr/news/paratash-notams-ews-tis-15-maioy-2020|title=\u03a0\u03b1\u03c1\u03ac\u03c4\u03b1\u03c3\u03b7 \u039d\u039f\u03a4\u0391\u039cS \u03ad\u03c9\u03c2 \u03c4\u03b9\u03c2 15 \u039c\u03b1\u0390\u03bf\u03c5 2020.|date=15 April 2020|work=|accessdate=21 April 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|page=|via=}}</ref> and land borders with Albania, North Macedonia and Turkey are closed, with exemptions for cargo and sanitary transports, among others.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.news247.gr/politiki/koronoios-ektakta-metra-kleinoyn-ta-synora-me-alvania-kai-v-makedonia-tilefonima-mitsotaki-se-ieronymo.7602425.html|title=\u0395\u03ba\u03c4\u03b1\u03ba\u03c4\u03b1 \u03bc\u03ad\u03c4\u03c1\u03b1 - \u039a\u03bf\u03c1\u03bf\u03bd\u03bf\u03ca\u03cc\u03c2: \u039a\u03bb\u03b5\u03af\u03bd\u03bf\u03c5\u03bd \u03c4\u03b1 \u03c3\u03cd\u03bd\u03bf\u03c1\u03b1 \u03bc\u03b5 \u0391\u03bb\u03b2\u03b1\u03bd\u03af\u03b1 \u03ba\u03b1\u03b9 \u0392. \u039c\u03b1\u03ba\u03b5\u03b4\u03bf\u03bd\u03af\u03b1 - \u03a0\u03b1\u03c1\u03ad\u03bc\u03b2\u03b1\u03c3\u03b7 \u039c\u03b7\u03c4\u03c3\u03bf\u03c4\u03ac\u03ba\u03b7 \u03b3\u03b9\u03b1 \u03c4\u03b9\u03c2 \u03b5\u03ba\u03ba\u03bb\u03b7\u03c3\u03af\u03b5\u03c2|website=www.news247.gr|language=el|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.gr/news/ellada/story/212372/koronoios-telos-apo-ta-mesanyxta-oi-ptiseis-apo-vretania-kai-toyrkia|title=\u039a\u03bf\u03c1\u03c9\u03bd\u03bf\u03ca\u03cc\u03c2: \u03a4\u03ad\u03bb\u03bf\u03c2 \u03bf\u03b9 \u03c0\u03c4\u03ae\u03c3\u03b5\u03b9\u03c2 \u03b1\u03c0\u03cc \u0392\u03c1\u03b5\u03c4\u03b1\u03bd\u03af\u03b1 \u03ba\u03b1\u03b9 \u03a4\u03bf\u03c5\u03c1\u03ba\u03af\u03b1|last=Newsroom|date=2020-03-23|website=CNN.gr|language=el|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref>\n\nThe measures put in place in Greece are some of the most proactive and strict in Europe and have been hailed internationally for slowing the spread of the disease and keeping the number of deaths among the lowest in Europe.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/05/world/europe/scientists-coronavirus-heroes.html|title=The Rising Heroes of the Coronavirus Era? Nations\u2019 Top Scientists|last=Stevis-Gridneff|first=Matina|date=5 April 2020|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lefigaro.fr/international/l-infectiologue-sotirios-tsiodras-nouvelle-coqueluche-des-grecs-20200320|title=L\u2019infectiologue Sotirios Tsiodras, nouvelle coqueluche des Grecs|last=Kefalas|first=Alexia|date=20 March 2020|website=Le Figaro.fr}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/opinion/articles/2020-04-07/stocks-rally-suggests-turning-point-in-coronavirus-fight|title=Stocks Rally Suggests Turning Point In Coronavirus Fight|last=|first=|date=|website=www.bloomberg.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/greeks-rein-in-rebellious-streak-as-draconian-measures-earn-them-a-reprieve-tznc0bn6s|title=Greeks rein in rebellious streak as draconian measures earn them a reprieve|last=Athens|first=Anthee Carassava|via=www.thetimes.co.uk}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ethnos.gr/kosmos/95931_ellinas-giatros-sto-mpermigham-protypo-i-ellada-i-bretania-se-heiroteri-thesi-apo-tin|title=\u0395\u03bb\u03bb\u03b7\u03bd\u03b1\u03c2 \u03b3\u03b9\u03b1\u03c4\u03c1\u03cc\u03c2 \u03c3\u03c4\u03bf \u039c\u03c0\u03ad\u03c1\u03bc\u03b9\u03b3\u03c7\u03b1\u03bc: \u03a0\u03c1\u03cc\u03c4\u03c5\u03c0\u03bf \u03b7 \u0395\u03bb\u03bb\u03ac\u03b4\u03b1, \u03b7 \u0392\u03c1\u03b5\u03c4\u03b1\u03bd\u03af\u03b1 \u03c3\u03b5 \u03c7\u03b5\u03b9\u03c1\u03cc\u03c4\u03b5\u03c1\u03b7 \u03b8\u03ad\u03c3\u03b7 \u03b1\u03c0\u03cc \u03c4\u03b7\u03bd \u0399\u03c4\u03b1\u03bb\u03af\u03b1|date=24 March 2020|website=\u0388\u03b8\u03bd\u03bf\u03c2}}</ref>\n\n=== Spain ===\n{{Main|2020 coronavirus pandemic in Spain}}\n{{Expand section|date=April 2020}}\nOn 31 January 2020, the first case was confirmed when a tourist tested positive for SARS-CoV-2 in [[La Gomera]], Spain.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Linde |first1=Pablo |title=Sanidad confirma en La Gomera el primer caso de coronavirus en Espa\u00f1a |url=https://elpais.com/sociedad/2020/01/31/actualidad/1580509404_469734.html |newspaper=El Pa\u00eds |accessdate=8 March 2020 |language=es |date=1 February 2020}}</ref> On 14 March, due to the increased number of cases, Spanish Prime Minister [[Pedro S\u00e1nchez]] declared a [[State of Alarm|state of alarm]], placing all citizens in quarantine except for those working in healthcare or other vital activities, closing all non-critical businesses, and only allowing citizens to go outside for activities such as grocery shopping or walking a pet.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rtve.es/noticias/20200313/pedro-sanchez-declara-estado-alarma-nacional/2009974.shtml|title=Pedro S\u00e1nchez declara el estado de alarma nacional|last=GRANDE|first=ROC\u00cdO GIL|date=2020-03-13|website=RTVE.es|language=es|access-date=2020-03-16}}</ref>\n==== Criticism of Spanish response ====\nSpanish government has received criticism for its perceived slow response to the pandemic, as it did not prevent any concentrations until 11 March when there already were 1,646 infected.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/25/how-spain-sat-on-its-hands-as-coronavirus-took-hold How coronavirus took just weeks to overwhelm Spain ] in ''[[The Guardian]]''</ref><ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/26/spain-coronavirus-response-analysis How did Spain get its coronavirus response so wrong?] in ''The Guardian''</ref> The large march in Madrid for International Women's Day (8 March), which was attended by around 120,000 people received special criticism, as this event was promoted and attended by members of the government such as [[Irene Montero]] who was later confirmed to be infected.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/europe/coronavirus-spain-nationwide-lockdown/2020/03/14/3bec8690-6619-11ea-8a8e-5c5336b32760_story.html|title=Spain goes on nationwide lockdown as coronavirus cases surge |access-date=15 March 2020 |date=15 March 2020 |newspaper=[[Washington Post]]}}</ref>\n\n=== United Kingdom ===\n{{Main|2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United Kingdom}}\n{{Expand section|date=April 2020}}\nOn 24 March 2020, the United Kingdom brought in \"some of the most far-reaching curbs on personal freedom ever introduced\" in peacetime, including a three-week lockdown of the country. This included a ban on public gatherings of more than two people (excluding those one lives with) and the closing down of all non-essential businesses.<ref>{{cite news |title=UK brings in strict curbs on life to fight virus |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-52014472 |accessdate=24 March 2020 |work=BBC News |date=24 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==== Criticism of British response ====\nThe UK government received intense pressure for its lax measures taken against the virus in comparison to other European countries.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/coronavirus-study-finds-uk-plan-could-cause-70000-excess-deaths-2020-3|title=The UK's slow response to the coronavirus could cause up to 70,000 excess deaths according to a new study|last=Colson|first=Thomas|website=Business Insider|access-date=6 April 2020}}</ref> The [[World Health Organization]] questioned the UK government's response to COVID-19 with spokeswoman Dr. Margaret Harris stating in an interview on ''[[Today (BBC Radio 4)|Today]]'' that not enough is known about the science of COVID-19 to justify the UK's approach to developing \"[[herd immunity]]\" against the virus, saying that while \"theories\" can be talked about, the current situation requires \"action\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cambridge-news.co.uk/news/uk-world-news/coronavirus-who-government-uk-strategy-17924466|title=World Health Organisation questions UK approach to COVID-19 outbreak|last=Leishman|first=Fiona|date=14 March 2020|website=Cambridge News|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=16 March 2020}}</ref> The UK's controversial plan to tackle COVID-19 has been developed by [[Patrick Vallance|Sir Patrick Vallance]] and [[Chris Whitty|Prof. Chris Whitty]].{{citation needed|date=March 2020}}\n\nGovernment Minister [[Helen Whately]] responded by saying that the Government is \"following the evidence\".{{citation needed|date=March 2020}}\n\n===Other countries and territories===\n{{div col|colwidth=15em}}\n\n* [[Image:Flag of Albania.svg|25px]] '''[[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Albania#Prevention measures|Albania]]'''\n* [[Image:Flag of Andorra.svg|25px]] '''[[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Andorra#Response|Andorra]]'''\n* [[Image:Flag of Austria.svg|25px]] '''[[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Austria#Prevention measures|Austria]]'''\n* [[Image:Flag of Belarus.svg|25px]] '''[[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Belarus#Government response|Belarus]]'''\n* [[Image:Flag of Belgium.svg|25px]] '''[[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Belgium#Government response|Belgium]]'''\n* [[Image:Flag of Bosnia and Herzegovina.svg|25px]] '''[[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Bosnia and Herzegovina#Measures|Bosnia and Herzegovina]]'''\n* [[Image:Flag of Bulgaria.svg|25px]] '''[[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Bulgaria#Response|Bulgaria]]'''\n* [[Image:Flag of Croatia.svg|25px]] '''[[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Croatia#Timeline|Croatia]]'''\n* [[Image:Flag of Czech Republic.svg|25px]] '''[[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Czech Republic#Policies to fight the contagion|Czech Republic]]'''\n* [[Image:Flag of Denmark.svg|25px]] '''[[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Denmark#Testing, treatment and preventive measures|Denmark]]'''\n* [[Image:Flag of Donetsk People's Republic.svg|